<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Reception Honors Sino-Japanese Relations  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese People's
Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries, together with
the China-Japan Friendship Association, hosted a reception here
this evening to mark the 25th anniversary of normalization of
diplomatic ties between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Qi Huaiyuan, president of the Chinese People's Association for
Friendship with Foreign Countries said in a speech that since the
normalization of Sino-Japanese ties 25 years ago, both countries
have witnessed a deep and comprehensive development in politics,
economy, science and technology, culture and exchanges between
their local governments, through the efforts by governments and
peoples of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral friendly cooperation has not only facilitated the
growth and prosperity of both nations but also contributed to the
peace, stability and prosperity of the Asia-Pacific region, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"We should remember those forerunners who have dedicated
themselves to the normalization of bilateral ties," Qi noted. The
Sino-Japanese relations have stepped into a new period, linking
the past with the future.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, the countries should abide by the
Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty of
Peace and Friendship, and work together to bring a sound and
stable bilateral friendly relationship into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan are two major powers in Asia and important
members in the international community, therefore to bring a sound
and stable Sino-Japanese relationship into the new century is not
only the common goal of the people of the two countries, but is
also essential to peace in Asia and the world at large, he stated.
</P>
<P>
Former Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who is here
for the celebrations in Beijing, told the group that remarkable
progress has been made in Japanese-Chinese relationship over the
past 25 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
