<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.2 Million Iraqis Die of Medicine Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.2 million Iraqis
died because of an acute shortage of medicines and medical
requisites over the six years of U.N. sanctions, Iraqi Health
Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak announced here today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference today Mubarak pointed out that health
conditions have continued worsening in Iraq as a result of lack of
medical supplies, such as the antiseptics and anesthetics which
are necessary for urgent surgeries.
</P>
<P>
In this period of time, Iraqi hospitals had to operate in about
one-third of their capacity, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
He held the U.N. Sanctions Committee responsible for delaying
the approval of the contracts concluded by Iraq with foreign
companies on the purchase of medical supplies under the
oil-for-food deal, which took into effect last December.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal signed between Iraq and the U.N. in May
1996 allows sanction-stricken Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of oil within six months to buy food and direly needed
medicines to ease the suffering of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The deal was renewed last June.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that Iraq used to import 500 million dollars worth
of medicines and medical requisites before the 1990 Gulf War, but
it imported medicines valued at only 7 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister also accused the United States and Britain
of using illegal weapons during the 1990 Gulf War, which has led
to an increasing number of leukemia infections, lymphatic gland
tumors and mental-retardation cases among Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanction against Iraq after President Saddam
Hussein sent troops to occupy Kuwait in August 1990. The troops
were driven out of Kuwait and defeated half a year later by the
U.S.-led coalition forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
