<HEADLINE> Beijing Reception Honors Sino-Japanese Relations  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said he personally aims to serve as a bridge for the future
bilateral ties, by helping Japanese young people, young statesmen
in particular, to learn more about China and to increase cultural
exchanges between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that Japanese-Chinese relations will continue
to flourish for the next 25 years, and that friendship between the
two countries will last from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
Yoshio Sakurauchi, chairman of the Japanese Association for the
Promotion of International Trade and former speaker of Japan's
House of Representatives, said that bilateral diplomatic relations
were normalized through the efforts of the past generations of the
two countries, and thanks to wise decisions of leaders of the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Japan and China have cooperated in a wide range of
areas such as politics, economy, culture and sports, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We should face up to and draw on lessons from history, and
look to the future, proceeding from the principaled stance set out
25 years ago," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also acknowledged that he will be devoted to carrying
forward the cause of Japanese-Chinese friendship.
</P>
<P>
The speeches of Qi, Takeshita and Sakurauchi all drew rounds
of applauses from the audience from both China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing, Vice-Chairman of the National
People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee Wang Guangying,
Vice-Chairmen of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) Wu Xueqian and Qian
Zhengying, as well as Honorary President of the Japanese
Federation of Economic Organizations Hiraiwa Gaishi were among
those present.
</P>
<P>
Other senior officials and businessmen from both China and
Japan also attended the reception.  
</P>
</TEXT>
