<HEADLINE> China Takes Asian Women's Volleyball Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- China trounced Japan 3-0 at
the last day of the 9th Asian Women's Volleyball Championship
Sunday to claim its sixth title in a row with all six match
victories.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, who had only lost to China here, beat Chinese
Taipei 15-5, 15-3, 15-10 in day's another championship round match
to take the runner-up .
</P>
<P>
China, led by Sun Yue who won the honor of the tournament's
best spiker and scorer, downed Japan 15-7, 15-9, 15-6 after
overcoming some challenges in the beginning of the first set,
where the scoring was 6-6 before the Chinese players took the lead.
</P>
<P>
"Our win was expected," said coach Lang Ping, who led the
Chinese team won the silver medal in the last year's Olympic
volleyball tournament. "My players are more experinced, but
Japanese girls could be very strong in two years."
</P>
<P>
Japan, who collected four wins and two losses, finished third,
whith Chinese Taipei fourth.
</P>
<P>
In day's consolation round matches, Thailand trounced Australia
3-0 (15-1, 15-4, 15-0) for fifth place while Uzbekistan beat
Philippines 3-0 (15-6, 15-8, 15-13) for sixth. Australia and
Philippines were seventh and eighth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
