<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Braces for Impending Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has set
aside over 1.5 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (125 million U.S.
Dollars) as a drought management fund in the mounting fears
over a possible drought during this rainy season.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the Ministry of Lands and Agriculture today told
the Zimbabwe News Agency that the government had enough
information on the looming drought, a result of the notorious El
Nino phenomenon, and was making every effort to ensure drought be
properly managed if it eventually occurred.
</P>
<P>
The money set aside would be used to ensure there is adequate
food for the country's estimated 12.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
"When the last devastating drought during the 1991/92 rainy
season occurred, we did not have any information, in fact we were
caught unawares. But this time the government has started to
prepare," said one official who declined to be named.
</P>
<P>
Kumbirai Kangai, Minister of Lands and Agriculture, recently
warned the farming community and the rest of the Zimbabwean
population to brace up for the drought, which he said could be
the worst in the history of the country.
</P>
<P>
Kangai said the country is fortunate this year to have enough
scientific information and indicators on the El Nino phenomenon
and the possible pending drought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
