<HEADLINE> Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The British government today
denied changing its policy on a single European currency, which
starts on January 1 1999.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting speculation that it was about to call a referendum on
British entry into European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU),
Chancellor Gordon Brown said on BBC Television that Britain would
make an announcement on its EMU intentions at the "appropriate
time...about the turn of the year".
</P>
<P>
He insisted that Britain's position on EMU has not changed
since the Labor Party came to power in May.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said: "It is unlikely Britain will
join in the first wave. There are formidable obstacles in the way
of doing so."
</P>
<P>
"If the single currency proceeds and if it is a success, then
in the longer term Britain could not stay out. But that is in the
longer term, it is not a little after," Cook said in another BBC
interview.
</P>
<P>
They were speaking after financial markets surged on Friday in
reaction to a Financial Times report which suggested that the
government was warming to the idea of EMU and that an announcement
on Britain entering the single currency would be made shortly.
</P>
<P>
A poll released Saturday showed that most people in Britain
remain resolutely opposed to joining a single European currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
