<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Israel-Palestinian Talks to Resume Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between Israel
and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) are expected to
resume soon, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told his
cabinet here today.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said at a cabinet meeting today that Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy and PNA chief negotiator Abu Mazen are now in
the United States and scheduled to meet with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright in New York Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the prime minister's office,
Netanyahu said he expected an agreement on reopening the peace
talks to be reached during that meeting.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, the PNA made some progress in fighting
against terrorism, which would be conducive to the resumption of
peace talks, the statement quoted Netanyahu as saying.
</P>
<P>
Today's cabinet meeting was called by Netanyahu to discuss the
impact of a nationwide general strike today and the recent
security cooperation between Israel and PNA.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has stepped up its campaign against the Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) and has reportedly arrested dozens of
its members and closed down 17 Hamas institutions, including a TV
station in Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said this is the initial step that PNA has taken
against terrorism and urged it to make more efforts.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Israel and PNA have been stalled since last
March following Israel's construction of a Jewish settlement in
Har Homa in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The peace process skidded into a deeper crisis after two
suicide bombing attacks in Jerusalem killed 25 people in July and
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
