<HEADLINE> International Community Urged to React to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Greek President Costis
Stephanopoulos today urged international organizations and the
great powers to react to Turkey's tactics of war threats.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in the northern Greek port city of
Thessaloniki today, the president accused Turkey of taking such
tactics, saying that they were directed not only against Greece
but international law and order, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the speech made by Turkish Deputy Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit that differences between Greece and Turkey
were not confined on the issue of Imia, an uninhabited island in
the Aegean, but included territorial waters, airspace, the
continental shelf and the militarization of islands.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos today also
criticized the Turkish policy, saying that Ankara's position was
"yielding diminishing results in the world stage."
</P>
<P>
"The whole issue," he said, "is developing now not as a Greek-
Turkish confrontation, but a confrontation between Turkey and the
international community."
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have since early this year been trying to
improve their strained relations for decades, but the war of words
between them are escalating following the breakdown of recent
talks between the two communities of Cyprus as well as between
Pangalos and his Turkish counterpart, Ismail Cem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
