<HEADLINE> PNA: No Peace Talks Without Solution To Settlements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks with Israel
will not be resumed without a solution to Jewish settlements in
West Bank and Gaza Strip, a senior official of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) said.
</P>
<P>
Marwan Kanafani, a spokesman for PNA President Yasser Arafat,
told the Voice of Palestine radio in Gaza that "there is no way
that negotiations (with Israel) will continue without a solution
to the Israeli settlement policy."
</P>
<P>
Kanafani's remarks were apparently the PNA's reaction to the
announcement earlier today by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu that Israel-PNA peace talks are expected to resume soon.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told his cabinet today that Israeli and PNA
officials will meet U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on
Monday in New York and are expected to reach an agreement to
reopen Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Kanafani had called it a "positive step in the right direction
if it's true."
</P>
<P>
However, now in a more cautious tone Kanafani urged Israel to
implement the interim agreement the two sides signed in 1995 under
which Israel has to redeploy in three stages its troops in West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The second stage troop redeployment had to be completed on
September 7, but so far Israel has done nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
Israel had announced to stop giving back lands to Palestinians
as long as they fell short of meeting Israeli demands for cracking
down on terrorist groups and dismantling their infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The PNA accused the Netanyahu government of attempting to rid
itself of the Oslo obligations of returning occupied territories
and retreating from the principle of "land for peace."
</P>
<P>
Kanafani pointed out the troop redeployment, a basic part of
the interim agreement which Israel failed to implement so far, has
been one of the main causes of the current crisis of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has stepped up its campaign in recent days against
Hamas and extremist militants, closing down 17 Hamas-affliated
institutions and rounding up 13 activists.
</P>
<P>
In a gesture of reciprocity, Netanyahu earlier today ordered
the release of more tax revenues Israel has been withholding since
the two suicide bombing attacks in Jerusalem in July and September
killed 20 Israelis and five bombers.
</P>
<P>
This transfer, together with the previous one in August, would
bring the total amount of revenues to be turned over to PNA to
over 25 million U.S. dollars, about half that Israel owes.
</P>
</TEXT>
