<HEADLINE> Partnership in Power Reforms to Be Focal Point of Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRIGHTON, England, September 28 (Xinhua) - The focal point of
the Labor Party conference this year is the vote on the proposed
Partnership in Power reforms, a Labor spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a pre-conference briefing for the media, the spokesman said
that the reforms is designed to build a successful partnership
between the party and the new Labor government.
</P>
<P>
The reforms focus on three main areas:
</P>
<P>
-- creating a policy-making process that is rational
</P>
<P>
and clear;
</P>
<P>
-- developing a party Conference which is modern and
</P>
<P>
inclusive;
</P>
<P>
-- electing an National Executive Committee that
</P>
<P>
reflects all parts of the party.
</P>
<P>
It is announced that a total of 1317 delegates and over 2000
journalists are attending the Labor Party Conference this year
which starts tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Among the 1317 delegates, 789 are from constituency parties, of
these, 414 are women, and 375 men.
</P>
<P>
Observers on the conference believe that Labor leader and Prime
Minister Tony Blair will issue a warning to delegates not to take
the support of voters for granted, in the first speech by a prime
minister to the Labor conference for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
"What the people give, the people can take away," the Prime
Minister will say at the Conference, according to the observers.
</P>
<P>
They also said that Blair wanted the conference to be about
Labor "getting on with governing". 
</P>
</TEXT>
