<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamas Threatens to Attack Overseas Israeli Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The military wing of the
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), responsible for recent
Jerusalem attacks, today threatened to move the battle abroad by
attacking Israeli targets around the world.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued today, Izzadin Kassim Brigades
strongly denounced Israeli secret intelligence service Mossad for
plotting the attack against a Hamas leader, Khalid Mashiel, in
Jordanian capital Amman last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mashiel, head of the political bureau of Hamas, was attacked by
two Canadian tourists with an electrical device in front of his
office in what Hamas called "an assassination attempt" by
Mossad. But Jordanian authorities downplayed the incident as the
result of a quarrel between his driver and the tourists.
</P>
<P>
Mashiel is recovering at a military hospital and his condition
is stable.
</P>
<P>
"The attempt of Mossad, through their collaborators, to
assassinate Khalid Mashiel, will cause us to move the battle
outside the borders of the nation," the Hamas release said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the leadership of the Izzadin Kassim are
"studying with great seriousness the response to this dangerous
crime by planned attacks against Israeli interests in different
parts of the world."
</P>
<P>
The release called planned retaliatory moves as "a legitimate
right and justified steps."
</P>
<P>
It called on Jordan's King Hussein to publicly punish those
responsible for the attack and cut off diplomatic relations with
the countries involved.
</P>
<P>
Izzadin Kassim also strongly denounced the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) for conducting the recent massive sweeps
of Hamas activists in the self-rule territories and demanded an
end to PNA corruption.
</P>
<P>
The release also threatened to carry out more terror
attacks. "Israel will pay dearly for its cowardice against our
brother Mashiel ... we will turn it into a fire to burn our
enemies and bombs to destroy the bodies of the murderers," it said.
</P>
<P>
Hamas claimed responsibility for the recent suicide bombing
attacks in Jerusalem, in which 25 people were killed and over 300
wounded.
</P>
<P>
The attacks have aggravated the already tense situation
between Israel and the PNA, and dimmed the hope for renewing the
peace process stalled since last March.
</P>
<P>
Israel, with the backing of the United States, is pressuring
the PNA to launch an all-out war against Hamas and other militant
organizations.
</P>
<P>
So far Israeli and Palestinian security forces have rounded up
hundreds of Hamas activists and other militants in operations
throughout the territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
