<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's PAC Founder Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Founder of South
Africa's Pan Africanist Congress (PAC) A. B. Ngcobo died on
Friday in a hospital here in the capital, his family spokesman
Sipho Mahamba said today.
</P>
<P>
Mahamba said in a statement that Ngcobo was imprisoned at
Pretoria Central Prison in the 1960s with the late Robert
Sobukwe, the first PAC President, and they were later joined by
Nelson Mandela, who is now President of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
At the time of his death, Ngcobo was advisor to Ben Ngubane,
Premier of the Kwazulu-Natal Province.
</P>
<P>
Ngcobo, born on July 20, 1931, was educated at the
universities of Natal-Durban, Witwatersrand and London.
</P>
<P>
During his years in exile, Ngcobo lived in Zambia, Tanzania,
Britain and the United States. He once taught at the University
of London, and the University of California, according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Ngcobo is survived by his wife Lauretta, three daughters and
two sons.
</P>
<P>
He will be buried in Ulundi, Kuazulu Natal Province, on the
coming Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
