<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Failed US Satellite Burns Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- An American out-of-control
earth observation satellite burned up in the atmosphere today, the
U.S. Space Command said.
</P>
<P>
The Lewis spacecraft, which started tumbling days after being
launched in August, crashed into the atmosphere at 27,000 kph and
burned up at 11:58 GMT over the southern Atlantic Ocean off the
coast of Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Agency (NASA) has
launched an independent investigation into the loss of the
mission, which was to have monitored land use and pollution.
</P>
<P>
"The Lewis satellite was not designed to survive re-entry and
is expected to have burned up in the atmosphere," said the U.S.
Space Command, which keeps track of nearly 8,000 orbiting objects.
</P>
<P>
The 65 million U.S. dollars Lewis mission was meant to be a
champion of NASA "cheaper, faster, better" philosophy, but four
days after launch it spun out of control and communications were
lost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
