<HEADLINE> Turkey Troops Continue Operation in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkish troops continued
cross-border operations against the Kurdish militants in northern
Iraq, despite strong criticism from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
A number of camps of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party, or
PKK, were destroyed in a week of air raids and ground offensives
by the Turkish troops, the Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Turkish fighter-bombers carried out an air strike on 15
suspected PKK camps Thursday in northern Iraq where more than
1,000 militants were reportedly gathering in preparation for
winter offensives into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
More than 8,000 Turkish troops, backed by 130 tanks, crossed
into northern Iraq to reinforce the units already stationed there
to wipe out PKK rebel camps. Anatolia said 138 rebels have been
killed so far.
</P>
<P>
Fighting was continuing in the regions of Kani Mazi, Ekmal,
Bervari, Meti, Carcel, Dergele in northern Iraq, it added.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops have frequently taken actions inside Iraq in the
past two years, triggering outcry from neighboring countries and
some international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Iran has called on Turkey to immediately withdraw its troops
from northern Iraq, saying the operations there increased
instability in the region, according to Iran's official news
agency.
</P>
<P>
However, a Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman said earlier
that the ongoing offensive against PKK rebels in northern Iraq is
only "a routine and limited action."
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 13-year-old separatist war against
the Turkish government in an attempt to establish an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
