Arafat arrived here Sunday afternoon for talks with Tunisian
president on the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Arafat and President Zine Al-Abidine Ben Ali
are scheduled on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat flew here from the Algerian capital of Algiers where he
discussed with President Liamine Zeroual on the same topics.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to reporters after meeting with Zeroual, Arafat
called on the Arab states to convene an emergency Arab summit to
examine the critical situation in Palestinian-Israeli relations.
</P>
<P>
Arafat underscored the importance of convening an Arab summit
as early as possible for a united Arab stand toward Israeli
hardline policies. He expressed hope that his appeal would meet
with "quick response" from all Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that he had briefed Zeroual during the meeting of
the difficult situation in Palestinian territories brought about
by Israel's refusal to implement the accords concluded with the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO).
</P>
<P>
He also said that Israel's closure imposed on Palestinian
territories and freezing millions of dollars in tax revenues due
to the Palestinian National Authority would not bring the
Palestinian (PNA) people to their knees.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Israel and PNA have been stalled since last
March after Israel's construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said earlier today
that he expected an agreement from a meeting Monday in New York
between Israeli and Palestinian officials and U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright on resuming peace talks after a six-month
freeze.
</P>
<P>
However, the Palestinian side said peace talks would not be
possible if without a solution to Jewish settlements. 
