<HEADLINE> France Warns US Against Rash Action over Total's Iran Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- France today warned the United
States against any rash action over the 2 billion U.S. dollar oil
deal signed Sunday by Iran and the French oil group Total.
</P>
<P>
"The application of the clauses of the (d'Amato) law will make
up in effect a grave precedent in the field of trade in
international law," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques
Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
He said the contact signed by Total "well appears to belong to
the activities that the d'Amato law aims to deter (international
companies) from undertaking" by making deals with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"The d'Amato law is America's. So it can only be applied in the
United States and upon American enterprises," the spokesman
pointed out, adding that only the United Nations Security Council
can decide to impose sanctions on individual countries and its
companies.
</P>
<P>
"The valid sanctions by international law are those taken by
the U.N. Security Council," he said, while recalling that France
and its European Union partners were strongly opposed to the law
when it came out last year on Capitol Hill in Washington DC.
</P>
<P>
"European Union and its member states have regularly expressed
their opposition to the principle of legislation carrying
unilateral sanctions with extra-territorial reach," he said.
</P>
<P>
The d'Amato law, adopted by the United States Congress and
signed by U.S. President Bill Clinton last August, aims to punish
American and foreign companies which make more than 40 million
dollars in deals with hydrocarbon and oil industries of Iran and
Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
