<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Spending Slows Despite Income Gain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The consumer spending in
the U.S. slowed in August despite a healthy personal income
increase, U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that personal consumption expenditures
increased by 0.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
5.52 trillion dollars in the month. That followed a 1 percent
surge in July, the biggest in six months.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in spending growth mainly resulted from the auto
sales. Spending on durable goods -- items expected to last three
or more years -- rose by 0.3 percent after a big 3.2 percent jump
in July. Spending on nondurable goods rose by 0.2 percent and on
services, by 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The department also said that U.S. personal incomes rose by 0.6
percent in August to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6.92
trillion dollars. It followed a 0.2 percent increase in July.
</P>
<P>
The disposable personal income -- income after taxes --
increased by 0.5 percent, a bit less than the overall gain.
</P>
<P>
The combination of robust income growth and a moderate spending
gain produced an increase in the U.S. savings rate -- savings as a
percentage of disposable personal income -- to 3.8 percent in
August from 3.6 percent in July which was a six-month low.
</P>
<P>
The report was the last major economic data released by the
U.S. government before the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) holds its
policy-making meeting on Tuesday. Most economists now expect that
the U.S. Fed will leave short-term interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed raised the short-term rate on March 25 but have
refrained since as inflation in the country has diminished despite
brisk economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
