<HEADLINE> Li Peng Visits Palace Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng
on Sunday visited the Palace Museum in Beijing, asking relics
officials and workers to do their utmost to protect the site.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by State Councilor Li Tieying, Beijing Mayor Jia
Qinglin and Culture Minister Liu Zhongde, Li visited a warehouse
of palace treasures and inspected a polluted moat surrounding the
Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
The Palace Museum, or the Forbidden City, is the site of the
home of many Chinese emperors. It was built some 500 years ago and
has been included on UNESCO's world heritage list.
</P>
<P>
After hearing a report by Zhang Wenbin, chief of the State
Cultural Relics Bureau, Li said that the Palace Museum is a museum
that has great influence both at home and abroad. As tourism
continues to develop, more and more people will come to visit it.
</P>
<P>
"We must let the masses of tourists view the relics
as often as possible on one hand, the management and
protection of relics must be strengthened on the other," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the policy of effectively protecting relics and
rationally making use of them must continue to be implemented, and
management must be stricter.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China is a civilized country with a long history
and abundant cultural relics. Therefore, the protection and
utilization of the relics are a duty-bound responsibility for
Chinese people. Government departments should attach great
importance to the work, he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier urged that a relics protection system be created in
accordance with the socialist market economy, to enable the
country's abundant cultural heritage to play a role in material
civilization and cultural and ethic progress.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
