<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Urged to Stick to Defense-Only Military Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korea urged Japan to
stick to defense-only military activities despite the new
Washington-Tokyo defense guidelines on the expansion of Japan's
military role in "crisis situations surrounding Japan."
</P>
<P>
Ryu Kwang-sok, Director-general of South Korea's Foreign Ministry
on Asia and Pacific Affairs, made the remark today during his
meeting with Kato Ryozo, Director-general of the Asian Affairs
Division of the Japanese Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Japan also agreed to conduct continuous consultations with
South Korea and maintain transparency in its negotiations with the
United States on strategies to implement defense guidelines, Ryu
said.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Kato explained to Ryu eight items in the
new defense guidelines which the Japanese government will not be
permitted, including engaging in any direct military activities
such as the provisioning of ammunition, or engine inspections of
U.S. warplanes or warships heading for battlefields, according to
Yonhap News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"Under guidelines recently amended, Japan will also not be
allowed to provide information on target selection," the Japanese
official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines allow Japanese forces to conduct inspections of
ships in international waters only with the approval of the United
Nations Security Council, Ryu noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the revised guidelines have yet to specify when, where
and how the Japanese self-defense forces will engage in crisis
situations.
</P>
<P>
Kato refused to categorize what constitutes "areas surrounding
Japan," saying that the areas are not a geographical concept but a
situational one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
