<HEADLINE> Iraq Condemns Iranian Air Raids on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Iraq strongly condemned Iran
today for its air raids on Iraqi territories, Iraq News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Eight Iranian warplanes bombed Monday morning camps of Iranian
opposition groups in areas of Diali province of Iraq, 80
kilometers east of Baghdad and Kute province, 180 kilometers south
of Baghdad, the agency quoted an Iraqi Foreign Ministry spokesman
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi anti-aircraft defense forces and warplanes resisted the
Iranian raiding planes, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Together with another country, Iran is taking advantage of
Iraq's hard conditions resulted from the U.N. blockade on Iraq to
launch air raids, it should be fully responsible for the
casualties and damages in Iraq caused by the raids, the spokesman
said, without giving the name of the other country, but apparently
referring to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been launching cross-border military operations in
northern Iraq to attack the Turkey's Kurdish rebels based in the
region since years ago. The lastest, which started in May is still
continuing.
</P>
<P>
Iran has also launched several air raids on northern Iraq
during the past years in a bid to wipe out some military posts of
the Iraq-based Iranian outlawed group Mujahedeen-e-Khalq (people's
holy warriors) Organization.
</P>
<P>
"Under such a state of affairs, the U.N. pledges to maintain
the sovereignty of Iraq have become ink and paper," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman called on the U.N. to keep its pledges to
maintain the sovereignty of Iraq in accordance with the relevant
U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the Arab nations and the international
community to denounce the Iranian aggression on Iraq, and to
pressure the U.S. and its allies to end the blockade imposed on
Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman emphasized that such aggressive behavior exposes
the falsity of Iran's call for dialog and peace with Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
