<HEADLINE> South Korea Pushes Inter-Korean Car Ferry Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The two Koreas and China are
negotiating a direct car ferry service as a way of developing
tourism in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) around
Mount Paekdu (Mount Changbai in Chinese), a South Korean
government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"South and North (DPRK) Korea and China are conducting talks on
opening a direct transit service between the South's Sokcho and
the DPRK's Rajin-Sunbong, both on the eastern coast. There is a
good possibility that progress will be made on the negotiations,"
Yonhap News Agency quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Ministry of Maritime Affairs and Fisheries,
DPRK's External Economic Affairs Commission and China's Ministry
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation are all involved in the
negotiations, which also covers customs regulations, he said.
</P>
<P>
If an agreement is reached among the three parties, South Korea
and China are likely to set up a joint-venture company, he said.
</P>
<P>
Seoul has been pursuing the idea of an inter-Korean sea route
after President Kim Young-sam declared in August that he is
willing to allow South Korean tourists to travel to the DPRK once
the four-party meeting opens.
</P>
<P>
The four-party talks, the probability of which remains
uncertain, is intended to bring together the two Koreas, the
United States and China to discuss peace and security on the
Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that while the maritime ministry is eager about
the idea, diplomatic and security-related agencies of the
government are not so keen on it because of the safety and
security issues it poses.
</P>
<P>
Seoul predicts 50,000 to 100,000 South Korean tourists would
visit Mount Paekdu, on the DPRK-Chinese border, and generate an
estimated 25 to 50 million U.S. dollars in foreign exchange income
for the DPRK in a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
