<HEADLINE> Singapore Welcomes Annan's Reform Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Singapore today hailed
the reform package of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
pledged to support his efforts to innovate the largest world
organization.
</P>
<P>
The position was indicated by Professor S. Jayakumar, Minister
for Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Singapore, in his address
at the general debate of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The debate of the 52nd session of the U.N. Assembly, which
began on last Monday, was focused on Annan's 29 reform measures
and 15 proposals put forward in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
"In the larger interests of this organization, we should all
welcome the thrust of the Secretary-General's proposals and not
take issue with too many details," Jayakumar said.
</P>
<P>
"By taking a pragmatic and eclectic approach we hope to help
move the reform process forward, even if we may have questions
about specific aspects," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Minister pledged to "continue to work with the
Secretary-General and other member states to make the UN a more
efficient and effective organization, one that will serve the
interests of all its members, big and small, developing as well as
industrialized."
</P>
<P>
However, Jayakumar noted some what he described as
"contradictions and ambiguities" in the proposals put forward by
some major powers for reforming the U.N. Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
