<HEADLINE> Guangzhou to Ban Use of Leaded Petrol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of
south China's economically-prosperous Guangdong province, will
prohibit vehicles in the city from using leaded petrol starting
October 1.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at reducing heavy pollution in the city
caused by auto emissions, according to regulations issued here
today by the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
Unleaded petrol will be available starting next month for
customers. Filling stations that continue to sell leaded fuel or
fuel which does not meet government standards will be fined a
maximum of 10,000 yuan, the regulations said.
</P>
<P>
Drivers who violate the regulations will also be fined, the
regulations added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in l995, some 473,000 tons of petrol were
used by vehicles in Guangzhou and some 740,000 tons of lead were
emitted into the atmosphere, accounting for five percent of the
national total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
