<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China's Stock Market Expected to Grow Stably </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Despite generally declining
stock indices, Chinese experts insist that they have good reasons
to be optimistic about the prospects of the country's stock market.
</P>
<P>
The main stock indices for China's two stock exchanges in
Shanghai and Shenzhen have been on a downward trend for more than
four months.
</P>
<P>
The reverse movement of the stock market against the sound
macro economic growth and upbeat forecasts, especially those in
recent weeks, has made investors hesitant about making new buying
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Many investors fear that the expected acceleration in market
expansion following the 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China, which endorsed a shareholding system in the
reforms of the State-owned enterprises, will result in an
oversupply of stocks. They also fear that many underperforming
enterprises will rush to the stock market to raise funds.
</P>
<P>
However, experts say that such fears are not justified, quoting
stock market administration sources as saying that China will
pursue not rash but stable advances in stock market development.
</P>
<P>
The stock market expansion will not be too rapid and companies
have to pass stern examinations for listing, they point out.
</P>
<P>
Jia Xiaoliang, an official in the State Economic and Trade
Commission, reaffirmed that only well-performing enterprises will
be listed.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the measures taken since last December by the
Chinese authorities to eliminate speculation, such as the
imposition of a ten percent ceiling on daily stock price movements
and banning bank credits from entering the stock market, are
intended to safeguard the market order and prevent small investors
from the woes of wild ups and downs in share prices.
</P>
<P>
Also, China has formulated more than 250 stock market laws,
rules and regulations, and investors' risk awareness has
increased considerably, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate institutional buying and a lack of investment funds
are two major factors affecting the stable development of China's
stock market, according to Zhang Houqi, deputy general manager of
the Research and Development Section of China Securities Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, Chen Yaoxian, chairman of the China
Securities Regulatory Commission, said earlier that China will
take measures to foster more institutional
investors. Well-informed sources say that details of the measures
will be announced soon.
</P>
<P>
China's share issue quota this year is 30 billion yuan, twice
the figure for last year. The quota for next year is estimated at
50 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
By the end of August, China had 708 listed companies, which had
a capital stock of 159.7 billion shares and a market
capitalization of 1.64 trillion yuan, about 24 percent of the
gross domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
