<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Japanese Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said
here today that China and Japan can bring good-neighborly and
stable bilateral ties into the 21st century only if the principles
set forth in the Sino-Japanese Joint Declaration and the
China-Japan Peace and Friendship Treaty are strictly followed.
</P>
<P>
Li made this remark during a meeting with a Japanese delegation
consisting of representatives from all walks of life, which was
led by former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and directors of
various Japan-China friendship organizations.
</P>
<P>
Li said that 25 years ago, the governments of the two countries
signed the renowned Sino-Japanese Joint Declaration and realized
the normalization of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
The then Japanese Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka, with his vision
and insight as a statesman, visited China and opened up a new
chapter of Sino-Japanese ties together with Chairman Mao Zedong
and Premier Zhou Enlai, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The present sound relationship, which has been hard-won,
reflects the long-term efforts of the statesmen of the former
generation and the people of the two countries, including those
present at the meeting, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 25 years, bilateral co-operation in various
sectors has progressed rapidly, he said. The Chinese government,
pursuing an independent foreign policy of peace, attaches special
importance to its relations with the neighboring countries, and it
is China's consistent policy to develop its relationship with
Japan, China's close neighbor, which is linked by a narrow
strip of water, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed the guests on the gist of the 15th National
Congress of the Chinese Communist Party which was held earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
Takeshita said this year marks the 25th anniversary of the
normalization of diplomatic relations; the 20th anniversary of the
signing of the Peace and Friendship Treaty is next year, and it is
of great significance for both countries to push forward bilateral
ties by celebrating the two big events.
</P>
<P>
He said he totally agrees with a Chinese saying that "when you
drink the water, think of those who dug the well." The present
bilateral relationship reflects the arduous efforts of several
generations, and the present generation shoulders the
responsibility to pass on the traditional friendship to the next
generation with a goal of achieving a lasting relationship, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Yoshio Sakurauchi, chairman of the Japanese Association for the
Promotion of International Trade, and other Japanese guests said
they look forward to Li's official visit to Japan this November,
and expressed the conviction that the visit will further promote
bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
