<HEADLINE> ADB Gives Loans to India, Kyrgyz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) today approved loans totaling 113 million U.S. dollars and a
technical assistance grant of 1.59 million U.S. dollar to
rehabilitate and expand two major Indian ports.
</P>
<P>
The Bombay and Madras Ports Project will support
commercialization and corporatization of selected major ports and
a privatization policy for the port sector, the ADB said in a news
release.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank today also approved two concessional
loans totaling 32.7 million dollars to help Kyrgyz Republic reform
and strengthen its education system.
</P>
<P>
The first loan of 19 million dollars will provide program
support for key government reforms in the policy areas of the
education sector. The second loan of 13.7 million dollars will be
used for an investment project to assist the reform.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ADB will provide a 930,000 U.S. dollar
technical assistance grant from the Japan Special Fund to
strengthen the capacity for education policy planning in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
