<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Residential Mortgage Slows in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's new residential
mortgage activity slowed in August, with gross new loans made
during the month fell sharply by 23.3 percent to 24.9 billion HK
dollars (3.19 billion U.S. dollars), after the rise of 27.3
percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Results of the latest monthly survey conducted by the Hong Kong
Monetary Authority (HKMA) show that the amount of outstanding
mortgage loans rose more slowly, by 2.3 percent to 406.9 billion
HK dollars (52.17 billion U.S. dollars) in August, compared to the
3.9 percent increase in July.
</P>
<P>
The annualized rate of growth of outstanding loans in the three
months to August decreased to 41.2 percent from 43.9 percent in
July. The average change over the last 12 months increased to 31.7
percent from 29.8 percent in July, according to the results.
</P>
<P>
Gross loans for the purchase of properties in the mainland
decreased to 285 million HK dollars (36.54 million U.S. dollars)
in August from 369 million HK dollars (47.31 million U.S. dollars)
in July. The amount of outstanding loans increased by 2.18 percent
to 7.13 billion HK dollars (0.91 billion U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
