<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photo Show Features China in Foreigners' Eyes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition of photos taken
by foreigners who live in or have visited China opened here today
to mark the 48th anniversary of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The exhibit, named "China Through Foreigners' Eyes," presented
300 foreigners' photos of China. They were selected from some
1,500 photos offered by over 500 photographers from more than 60
countries.
</P>
<P>
The photos in the show cover almost every aspect of Chinese
society, painting a fairly complete picture of China's reform and
opening-up drive, social progress and people's everyday life.
</P>
<P>
Some of the pictures illustrated the three major events in
China's political life this year: the death of senior leader Deng
Xiaoping, the return of Hong Kong to the motherland and the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China. Other photos
reflected the daily routines of Chinese people's life, such as the
morning exercise of a centenarian.
</P>
<P>
And many pictures focus on the country's picturesque landscape,
rich cultural heritage and colorful folk customs.
</P>
<P>
"This photo show is intended to help develop the friendship
between the Chinese people and peoples in the rest of the world,
thus making the world a more peaceful and beautiful place," one of
the show's organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Today's show, jointly sponsored by the All-China Journalists'
Association, Chinese Association for Cultural Exchanges with
Foreign Countries, Xinhua News Agency and 15 other units, is the
fifth of its kind in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The first "China Through Foreigners' Eyes" photo show was
staged in Beijing in 1987. It was named after a special column
opened 16 years ago in a Beijing-based "Bridge Magazine," which
was sponsored by the All-China Journalists' Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
