<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK People More Confident in Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The latest bimonthly public
opinion survey conducted by Hong Kong's Home Affairs Bureau has
revealed a more buoyant mood and confident outlook among the
people of Hong Kong as compared with previous survey findings.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted over the telephone, showed that 80
percent of the respondents were confident that Hong Kong would
continue to be prosperous and stable, which is eight percentage
points higher than a similar survey conducted in July.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 82 percent expected the situation to improve or
remain unchanged in the coming 12 months, which is also up by
eight percentage points.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the survey said this optimistic outlook was
collaborated by the finding that only four percent of the 1,033
respondents considered Hong Kong's future to be a problem, which
is lower compared to eight percent in the last survey.
</P>
<P>
He added that 81 percent of the respondents were satisfied with
the present situation, which is four percentage points higher than
in the last survey.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the positive outlook appeared to have carried
over to the public's perception of government performance, which
has won the approval of 53 percent of the people, representing a
three percentage point improvement.
</P>
<P>
Of the three most often mentioned problems, housing remains on
top of the list at 63 percent, followed by social welfare related
and labor-related problems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
