<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Statement of Sino-U.S. Joint Economic Committee (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A joint statement was issued
following the 10th Session of the China-United States Joint
Economic Committee which was held on September 26 while the
U.S. Secretary of Treasury Robert E. Rubin visited China. The
full text of the Joint Statement is as follows:
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of the Chinese Finance Minister Liu Zhongli,
U.S. Secretary of Treasury Robert E. Rubin visited China and
co-chaired the 10th Session of the China-U.S.Joint Economic
Committee (JEC). Chinese leaders met with Secretary Rubin during
his visit and discussed the issue of promoting bilateral relations
and other issues of common interest in a friendly atmosphere.
Secretary Rubin passed on a letter from President Bill Clinton
to President Jiang Zemin, and discussed with President Jiang the
economic issues related to President Jiang's forthcoming state
visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
During the JEC meeting, senior officials from both sides held
extensive discussions on a broad range of economic issues. The two
ministers noted that the mutual understanding and relationship in
the economic, financial, and law enforcement fields between the
two countries have been enhanced through regular dialogues in the
JEC and other international and regional forums. They stressed
their common desire to strengthen the relations and cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The 10th Session of the JEC, was held in the form of plenary
and three subgroups, dealing with macroeconomics and trade, the
financial sector, and law enforcement issues, respectively.
</P>
<P>
On macroeconomics and trade, both sides reviewed the policies
that have contributed to their strong growth and moderate
inflation, and discussed the challenges they face in sustaining
this performance. The United States pointed to prudent fiscal and
monetary policies on its side, and to the significant
restructuring of U.S. industry that had occurred in recent
years. China discussed its balancing of aggregate demand and
supply and continued fiscal and financial stability during the
process of deepening reform. The two sides discussed the complex
issues of social welfare policies and restructuring of state-owned
enterprises in the context of reform and sustainable economic
growth. They also discussed the benefits of foreign investment in
the two countries, and the types of steps they might take to
ensure that their investment environments remain attractive.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed the external positions of both
countries, as well as bilateral imbalances between them. They
discussed China's exchange rate and the growth of its reserves, as
well as exchange rate policy of the United States. In addition,
the two sides discussed China's accession to the WTO, including
the role financial services, and how progress can be accelerated
consistent with WTO rules and obligations. The two sides also
discussed the roles of the two countries in the regional and
global financial systems.
</P>
<P>
The discussion on the financial sector focussed on developments
in the two countries' markets as well as on issues of regulation
and supervision and how the two countries could cooperate to
improve them. The Chinese side noted the steps they have taken to
strengthen their bank regulatory system, and explained their plans
for continuing this process. The two sides also discussed market
access for financial institutions in each country, and the
importance of free flows of information to financial markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
