<HEADLINE> Joint Statement of Sino-U.S. Joint Economic Committee (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Law enforcement issues included improving cooperation on
combating financial crimes, money laundering, and customs
violations. The two sides noted the laws in both countries that
apply to exports and imports of goods made by prison labor. They
discussed ways that both sides could strengthen their cooperation
under existing agreements to enforce their laws in this area.
</P>
<P>
Minister Liu Zhongli pointed to the following developments
that have taken place since the last JEC meeting:
</P>
<P>
-- China had decided to accelerate the reform of state-owned
enterprises and readjust and improve their ownership structure;
</P>
<P>
-- Referring to China's acceptance of Article VIII of the IMF
Articles of Agreement, he observed that the move represented a
significant step forward in the opening of the Chinese economy. He
noted that it would lead to the full convertibility of the
Renminbi (RMB) in the future, furthering the economic integration
of China with the rest of the world;
</P>
<P>
-- By granting licences to a number of foreign banks to conduct
RMB-business in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai, the Chinese
government has taken concrete actions to further open China's
financial market to foreign financial institutions which meet the
requirements for being engaged in such businesses;
</P>
<P>
-- The General Administration of Customs of China has resumed
discussions with the U.S. Customs Services on a Customs Mutual
Assistance Agreement, which both sides expected would lead to the
conclusion of an agreement before the next JEC through joint
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Rubin welcomed all of these developments and made
remarks on a number of following specific issues:
</P>
<P>
--He welcomed China's statement that it would protect the
rights and interests of overseas-funded enterprises and grant them
national treatment in order to permit competition on an equal
footing;
</P>
<P>
-- He welcomed China's active participation in the
international financial system. He took note of China's
contributions to the recent financial package for Thailand, and
welcomed China's interest in joining the Inter-American
Development Bank and the Bank for Economic Cooperation and
Development in the Middle East;
</P>
<P>
-- He reiterated the hope that the relations between the
U.S. Treasury and the Chinese Finance Ministry would continue to
develop, and he noted that there has been a significant expansion
of contacts between officials of the two departments. He took note
of the technical cooperation that the Treasury and other
U.S. agencies have undertaken with Chinese agencies, and indicated
that such cooperation should continue;
</P>
<P>
Secretary Rubin and Minister Liu agreed that the next meeting
of the JEC would be held in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation to the JEC consisted of representatives
from the Ministry of Finance, the People's Bank of China, the State
Planning Commission, the State Economic and Trade Commission, the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, the General Administration of Customs, the
State Administration of Foreign Exchanges and the China Securities
Regulatory Commission. The U.S. delegation included
representatives from the Department of the Treasury, the Federal
Reserve Bank, the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative, the
U.S. Customs Service, and the U.S. Embassy in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
