<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Gov't Starts to Sell its Final Stake in Lufthansa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 29 (Xinhua) -- German national airline Lufthansa
has reached its final stage of privatization as the German government
today started to sell its remaining 35.7 percent stake in the company.
</P>
<P>
The placement of 143 million Lufthansa shares held by the
government represents the second-largest stock flotation in German
history after last year's privatization of the state-owned telecom
giant Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
The share subscription offer is due to last until October 10 when
the final sales price will be announced.
</P>
<P>
On the current prices of around 36 marks (21 U.S. dollars), stock
experts predicted that the Bonn government was likely to make some 4.5
billion marks (2.6 billion dollars) from the sale.
</P>
<P>
The Lufthansa stock flotation is part of Bonn's efforts to boost
government revenues and to increase the country's chance to meet the
fiscal standards required for joining the planned single European
currency, the Euro, in January 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
