<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Commercial Bank Office Opened in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A commercial bank office
was opened here today, the first since the United Arab Emirates
banned such banks in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Bankers said the opening of the representative office of the
Bahrain-based Arab Banking Corporation indicates an approaching
revision of the ban on new commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
"I think the Central Bank of the UAE has begun to revise the
ban on new commercial banks because the market has sharply grown,"
a banker in the UAE's Abu Dhabi Commercial Bank told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The UAE introduced the ban amid fierce strong competition among
banks seeking a bigger share of the market in the oil-rich state,
which is classified as over-banked.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that despite its relatively low
population of 2.4 million, the UAE has 47 banks, 28 of which are
foreign-owned, with a total capital of some 63.4 billion
U.S. dollars at the end of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
