<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading American newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- The rate of cancer among American children has been rising
for decades. Many experts suspect that the increase may be partly
the result of growing exposure to new chemicals in the
environment. That suspicion, while still unproven, is beginning to
shape Federal research priorities and environmental strategies.
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli and Palestinian leaders said they expected that a
meeting today with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in New
York would help revive talks on a range of issues. Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel said that the Palestinian Authority
had taken "preliminary steps" in cracking down on militants, and
he released 17 million U.S. dollars that had been withheld from
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Russian organized crime groups flush with dollars, are
forming alliances with Colombian drug traffickers in the
Caribbean, acquiring cocaine for delivery to Europe and providing
weapons to Latin American mafias, according to U.S. European and
Latin American law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
-- The first of the showdowns between the tobacco industry and
the U.S. states that have sued it begins today in a Texas federal
courtroom. Taxas is asking for 8.6 billion U.S. dollars in the
case, claiming that the tobacco industry concealed information
about the health effects of tobacco and the addictiveness of
nicotine.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Congress hopes to pass a stopgap bill before fiscal 1997
ends tomorrow, having finished only three of 13 spending measures.
Included is a three-week delay in a deadline for undocumented
immigrants to seek residence. Republican leaders Friday agreed to
boost Environment Protection Agency funds in return for more
spending in GOP districts.
</P>
<P>
-- Minorities account for 29 percent of new home-owners in the
past three years, according to an analysis of Census figures by
the Kennedy School of Government. The report also says that the
number of minority home-owners increased 38 percent from 1985 to
1995. 
</P>
