<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Manufacturers Score Economy Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Despite some positiveurers
trend in the Nigerian economy, the country's manufacturers have
described the overall performance of economy as below
expectations.
</P>
<P>
In its half-year economic report released at the weekend, the
Manufacturers Association of Nigeria (MAN) said: "apart from
local raw materials sourcing which rose from 54 percent to 58
percent, all other indicators maintained a disturbing downward
trend."
</P>
<P>
Some 11,907 jobs were swept away between January and June this
year, a drop of 12 percent from 48,909 by December last year in
the sector, which also witnessed a 26.3 percent fall in
investment.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers' unsold inventory swelled to 4.6 billion Naira
(about 55 million U.S. Dollars), 13.7 percent over 3.97 billion
Naira (some 48 million Dollars) at the end of last year,
according to MAN.
</P>
<P>
But it was a drop compared with 6.033 billion Naira (some 73
million Dollars) in the first half of last year.
</P>
<P>
MAN statistics also revealed that capacity utilization in
companies also declined to 29.35 percent by June this year from
33.94 percent from the second half of last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, industrial output correspondingly narrowedurers
to 31.4 billion Naira (about 378 million Dollars), compared with
33.7 billion Naira (about 406 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The five sub-sectors hit hardest by reduced capacity
utilization are those of textiles, wearing apparels, leather
products and carpets; wood and wood products; non-metallic
products; plastic, rubber and foam products; and electrical and
electronic products.
</P>
<P>
Citing the petrol shortage in the economic center of Lagos and
environs as well as the failure in the refineries, the
non-governmental organization further said that the 5.5 percent
growth target in the country's gross domestic product projected
in the 1997 budget may not be met.
</P>
<P>
So far there is no government report on the economic
performance of the country in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the achievements resulted from government
macro-economic control have been widely accepted in the country,
including the manufacturing sector which accounts for an
approximate 10 percent of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Earlier statistics show that inflation rate dropped from 28
percent at the end of last year to 15.7 percent by July this
year, while foreign exchange reserves came up from 4.08 billion
Dollars to 7.4 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the local currency to the Dollar has also
been stabilized.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact, the national economy has not been bounced
back, according to Finance Minister Chief Anthony Ani.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of bankers last month, Ani acknowledged that real
growth was still below expectations and the government needed to
promote it by encouraging foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the government's commitment to provide the
much-needed enabling environment for investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
