<HEADLINE> Nigeria Begins Gas Export to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today began to export
liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) to the U.S. from Escravos in the
south, marking a major achievement in developing its huge natural
gas resources.
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian Tribune report said the Escravos gas project, a
joint venture between the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation
and the Chevron Nigeria Limited, is now utilizing 165 million
standard cubic feet of associated gas daily.
</P>
<P>
Besides exporting 8,000 barrels of LPG daily to the U.S.
market, the project in the Delta State has also started supplying
dry gas to the Nigerian Gas Company, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Escravos gas project was started in 1991. Total investment
involved is estimated at 569 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is blessed with 110 trillion cubic feet of gas
reserve, the 10th largest in the world. However, it is estimated
that about 70 percent of the associated gas produced in the
country's oil fields are being flared.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Escravos gas project, several other gas
projects are under construction, including the Nigeria Liquefied
Natural Gas Project with an investment of 3.6 billion US Dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
