<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Airports Are Danger Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Three major Nigerian airports
have been tagged danger zones by the International Federation of
Airline Pilots Association, the Nigerian Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
The three airports are, Muritala Muhammed international
airport in Lagos, the Aminu Kano international airport in Kano
and the Port Harcourt international airport in River State.
</P>
<P>
The association dubbed the three airports into class three
critically deficient airports during its recent 33rd general
meeting in Accra, Ghana, where it viewed over 80 airports in
Africa and the Middle East, the report said.
</P>
<P>
This classification means the airports are below the
international civil aviation organization safety standard
concerning the provision of navigational facilities and aids, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
In a reaction to this development, the report said, the
Nigerian National Association of Aircraft Pilots and Engineers
also expressed similar concern over the poor state of airports in
the country.
</P>
<P>
"Our association hopes to work closely with the management of
the Federal Airports Authority of Nigeria and the Federal
Ministry of Aviation to correct this worrisome situation," it
said in a news release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
