<HEADLINE> Israel's Unemployment Reaches Three-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Israel's unemployment
rate reached a three-year high of 8 percent in July and August,
according to an initial data published today by the Israeli
Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate is far more higher than Israeli Treasury's
most pessimistic figures, which suggested the unemployment rate
would be at 7.7 percent by December 31 this year and 7.9 percent
12 months later.
</P>
<P>
The data showed the people out of work numbered 180,000
respectively in July and August, compared with 168,000 on average
during the second quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
According to the data, 41,000 people have joined the ranks of
the unemployed since the beginning of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury also predicted two sets of figures for
unemployment by 2000. In the optimistic view, the jobless rate will
decline to 6.8 percent, but in the worst case, 11.4 percent of
the workforce will be unemployed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
