<HEADLINE> Chinese, Japanese PMs Exchange Greetings on Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng and
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto today exchanged messages
of congratulation on the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
Sino-Japanese diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li noted that in the past 25 years since the
normalization of Sino-Japanese diplomatic relations, marked
progress has been achieved in bilateral relations through the
concerted efforts of the two governments and the two peoples from
all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
This has not only brought about great benefits to the two
countries, but also made important contribution to peace,
stability and development in this region and the world at large,
Li said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Premier stressed that the bilateral relations,
which have developed into such a hard-won but good situation at
present, should be cherished by both sides.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China and Japan are important neighboring
countries and major economic cooperation partners of each
other. When the world is moving fast toward multi-polarization, it
is of great significance for the two countries to strengthen their
good-neighborly relations of cooperation looking into the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li said he hoped the two countries will take advantage
of the 25th anniversary of normalization of relations to make
continued efforts to ensure that the bilateral relations will
develop in a healthier and more stable way on the basis of the
Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the Treaty of Peace and
Friendship between the People's Republic of China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Prime Minister Hashimoto said China and Japan
realized the historic normalization of bilateral relations on the
very day 25 years ago. Since then, the two sides have surmounted
different social systems and achieved friendly cooperative
relations in various fields.
</P>
<P>
During his recent visit to China, Hashimoto said, he and his
Chinese counterpart recalled the development of the bilateral
relations since the normalization of their diplomatic relations,
and reached a consensus that in the following 25 years, the two
sides should strengthen dialogue and deepen cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Hashimoto expressed confidence that the
exchanges of visits between leaders of the two countries will help
the Sino-Japanese relations develop in a broader and more
extensive way.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese side is willing to work together with the Chinese
side to bring the Sino-Japanese friendly relations into the 21st
century, Hashimoto said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
