<HEADLINE> Liberian President Presents Budget to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor has presented a 12-million-U.S.-dollar interim budget to
parliament for approval.
</P>
<P>
No information is available on the allocation of funds in the
budget to the various government ministries and agencies, but
Taylor said the money would service some nine months' salary
arrears to civil servants.
</P>
<P>
The budget for the September-December period of this year also
covered logistics and development, according to a report reaching
here today.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, who described the budget as deficit free, said the
budget would be funded from the collection of revenues, including
customs, excise taxes and the maritime fund -- the only current
foreign exchange earner for the government, which was inaugurated
in August.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to parliament dominated by members of his ruling
National Patriotic Party, Taylor said he would maintain "sound
fiscal policy".
</P>
<P>
He also pledged to make up all salary arrears of civil
servants by December 31, which reports said earlier amounted to
about 30,000 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian government also faces a foreign debt of three
billion Dollars and a domestic debt of two million Dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
