<HEADLINE> Monument to Honor Afforestation Heroes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a monument
to those who have made outstanding contributions to China's
afforestation started here today.
</P>
<P>
The monument, standing in a forest in western suburban
Beijing. will bear the names of those who have planted most
trees and grasses and have achieved remarkable results
in forestry research and protection of forestry resources.
</P>
<P>
Names of some overseas Chinese and foreigners who have
concerned themselves with and provided financial help to China's
afforestation will also be carved on the monument, according to
Minister of Forestry Chen Yaobang who attended the ground-breaking
ceremony today.
</P>
<P>
Chen said China is greener than it was 15 years ago, and 12 out
of the country's 33 provinces and regions in the country have no
barren hills and the national forest coverage has been uplifted to
13.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, China still has 63 million hectares of wasteland and
waste hills that are suitable for planting trees. The forestry
coverage is only half of the world's average.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing tremendous challenges to reverse the trend of
worsening ecological system," Chen said, urging the people of the
whole country to be more responsible and make greater concerted
efforts to make the country greener.  
</P>
</TEXT>
