<HEADLINE> More Palestinian Workers Allowed to Enter Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Israel Army announced today
to allow additional 8,000 Palestinian workers to enter Israel
starting this morning in a move to help reactivate the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
This brought the total number of Palestinian workers allowed
in to 29,000, who had been barred from entering the country since
Israel imposed a total closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip
after the September 4 suicide bombing attacks in Jerusalem,
which killed eight people and wounded nearly 200 others.
</P>
<P>
Israel began to ease the closure gradually two weeks ago in
response to the security cooperation from the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA), that has arrested more than 200 Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) activists in the recent roundup.
</P>
<P>
Israel's decision also comes at a time when Israel and the PNA
may resume direct talks in the framework of the Oslo accords in
the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Sunday that the
resumption of Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which have seen a
statemate since Israel started construction of a new Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem, was made possible by the
discussions held in Washington between Israeli and Palestinian
delegations.
</P>
<P>
An official announcement of the resumption of the peace talks
is expected today at the meeting in New York among Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy, PNA President Yasser Arafat's deputy Mahmoud
Abbas and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
In another positive step to push peace talks forward,
Netanyahu said that he has given instructions to the transfer to
the PNA 59 million shekels (about 16 million U.S. dollars), half
of the funds withheld by Israel since the Mahaneh Yehuda attack on
July 30.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side welcomed the positive measures taken by
the Israeli government. Arafat's spokesman Marwan Kanafani said
that "the Israeli government agreed to resume the negotiations
committees and we see this as a positive step in the right
direction." 
</P>
</TEXT>
