<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Vows to Boost Ties With Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today vowed to expand cooperative relations with China
and other neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto made the pledge in a major policy speech to the 141st
extraordinary session of the Japanese Diet (parliament) which
opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the 25th anniversary of normalization of Sino-Japanese
diplomatic ties, Hashimoto expressed hopes for deepening dialogue
at various levels and strengthening trust between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"I want to establish friendly Japan-China relations, which can
contribute to the development of the Asian-Pacific region and the
whole world," Hashimoto said.
</P>
<P>
On domestic issues, Hashimoto reiterated his vow to push
through his six-point reform program, placing special emphasis on
the overhaul of a creaking government bureaucracy, which he said
has shown "serious limitations."
</P>
<P>
"Without administrative reform, I don't think we can gain the
trust of the people," said Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, who won his reelection as leader of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) earlier this month, reshuffled his
cabinet on September 11.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said reforms of Japan's administrative, fiscal,
social security, economic, monetary and education systems are his
cabinet's top priority issues.
</P>
<P>
"The cabinet will grapple intensively with the reforms during
the last three years of this century, so that all people can enter
the 21st century with pride and confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also pledged efforts toward reforming the
United Nations, and reaching an agreement on significant,
impartial and feasible targets for cuts in greenhouse gas
emissions at a U.N. climate change conference to be held in Kyoto
in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
