<HEADLINE> Saudi, Yemeni Border Dispute to be Solved Soon: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The decades-old border
dispute between Yemen and Saudi Arabia will be resolved once and
for all in a few weeks, Yemeni Interior Minister Hussein Moh'd
Arab has said.
</P>
<P>
The interior minister made the remarks in an interview with
local English daily Arab Times published today.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the delay in ending the border dispute
between the two countries mainly due to the Gulf War in 1991,
they succeeded in reaching common grounds on issues of security
and stability.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that negotiations between Yemen and Saudi
Arabia has led to positive results, adding that the leadership of
the two countries have the political will to solve the border
issue and mend the relationship between the two countries in
various fields.
</P>
<P>
"We are hopeful that the forthcoming weeks will witness new
positive developments in resolving the disputes between the two
countries, especially the border issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The border dispute between Yemen and Saudi Arabia dates back
to the 1960s when Britain ended its domination of the Gulf,
leaving ill-defined frontiers separating the countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been locked in border disputes since
then, but since February 1995 when the Memorandum of
Understanding concerning the solution of the border issues was
signed, tensions have been eased and bilateral ties have been
improving.
</P>
<P>
Saudi-Yemeni demarcation negotiations were launched
accordingly through joint committees formed in line with the
memorandum which laid the basis for a solution to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Intensified political efforts for the same purpose started
from July this year when Saudi and Yemeni interior ministers
exchanged letters from King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and Yemeni
President Ali Abdullah Saleh to exchange formulas of final
solution.
</P>
<P>
The latest effort on solving the issue was the Yemeni interior
minister's visit to Saudi Arabia on August 9 to pave the way for
an expected visit by Saleh to Saudi Arabia to solve the border
disputes between the two neighboring Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Saleh paid his second visit to Saudi Arabia in two years in
early February to discuss issues of border demarcation between
the two countries and hold talks with Saudi leaders on bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed security and economic agreements
last year to boost bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Honors Foreign Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A meeting was held here today
to confer 1997 Friendship Awards on 45 foreign experts for their
outstanding contribution to the development of China's economic
construction, science, technology and culture.
</P>
<P>
The State Bureau of Foreign Experts selected this year's
winners from over 80,000 foreign experts working throughout
China. This year's group of winner's included 12 experts in the
cultural and educational sector, 29 in economics, technology and
management, and four representatives from experts organizations
abroad.
</P>
<P>
The winners ranged between the ages of 35-74 and many have
worked in China for as long as a decade.
</P>
<P>
In an address at the awarding meeting, Chinese Vice-Premier Zou
Jiahua said the introduction of foreign expertise and experience,
as well as exchanges of skilled personnel and international
cooperation in economics, science, culture, education and other
areas are major measures of China's modernization drive. The
policy will remain unchanged in the future, said Zou.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier noted that China is still a developing country
with relatively backward scientific and technological levels. He
added that the foundation of China's economy is relatively weak
and the overall quality and efficiency of the national economy is
relatively weak.
</P>
<P>
China still lags behind developed nations and it is imperative
that the nation absorb and learn from the achievements of mankind
as a whole, said Zou.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that more foreign experts will become
involved in China's reform, opening and modernization efforts, and
added that China will continue to send technicians and management
personnel for study and training in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China invited some 570,000 foreign experts
to work in the country between 1979-1996. Over 80,000 foreign
experts are expected to come to work in China this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
