<HEADLINE> Japan's Diet Opens 141st Extra Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Diet (parliament)
opened the 141st extraodinary session today with debate expected
to focus on new guidelines for Japan-U.S. cooperation and the
government's reform program.
</P>
<P>
High on the agenda of the 75-day session is the new
Japan-U.S. Defense Cooperation Guidelines, released last week in
New York.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines paves the way for Japan to provide a wide
range of logistic and noncombatant support to the U.S. military in
peacetime and in emergencies "in areas surrounding Japan."
</P>
<P>
The Diet session seems unquiet as opposition parties threatened
to submit a non-confidence motion against Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's cabinet for the recent resignation of Koko Sato as
Management and Coordination Agency chief. They said Hashimoto
should take the blame for the appointment of Sato who was
convicted in 1986 of taking bribes in the 1970s Lockheed payoff
scandal.
</P>
<P>
They also threatened to boycott debate at all Diet Committees
unless an Osaka dealer, who claims to have donated political funds
to six politicians of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party, is
summoned and questioned during the Diet session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
