<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Defense Industry: Turning Swords into Ploughshares (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- On streets of many Chinese
cities, mini-van taxis are very popular and convenient
transportation tools for ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
For every 10 such taxis, seven are manufactured by former
weapons factories. These factories also turn out one fifth of the
total national output of cameras and almost two thirds of
motorcycles. Even the rice on the dinner table may be one of the
325 kinds of grains that have been treated by nuclear radiation
technology, formerly the preserve of the military.
</P>
<P>
Two decades ago, Chinese people's knowledge of the defense
industry was limited to a number of factories with names
mysteriously coded in Arabic numerals to protect their
identity. Today people are only too familiar with it through its
civilian products throughout their daily life, from cars and color
TV sets to tiny dress buttons.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a massive effort to turn swords into ploughshares
that started in the early 1980s, the Chinese people are now able
to enjoy all the material benefits brought by a converting defense
industry.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the defense industry now manufactures 15,000 kinds of
civilian products in the fields of communication, transportation,
energy, light industry, medicine, textile, engineering and
construction. Civilian products accounted for 80 percent of the
total output value generated by the industry in 1996, with an
average growth rate of 20 percent in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The defense industry is expected to claim a bigger share of the
country's merchandise market. "For one thing, weapons factories
enjoy a good reputation for quality and credibility," said Zhang
Junjiu, president of the China National Ordnance Industrial
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The industry's potential for further development is based on
its strength. Before 1979, massive amounts of money had been spent
constructing what was called the "Third Front," a strategic rear
base in central and southwestern China with numerous new weapons
factories.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1978, China's defense industry had a huge amount
of assets and employed three million scientists, engineers and
workers. Its factories were fed by orders from a huge army and did
not have to worry a bit about hunger.
</P>
<P>
Good times came to an end abruptly in 1985, when China reduced
its defense forces by one million troops and cut down on
procurement of military products. The defense industry was called
upon to turn to civilian production for survival and
self-development.
</P>
<P>
A number of defense factories moved out of their hiding places
right into center of economic activities, such as coastal cities.
</P>
<P>
Though facing difficulties brought by the transition of a
planned to a market economy, defense industry had three things
they could count on in their efforts to produce civilian
goods: high technology, ample labor and good reputation.
</P>
<P>
These factors have turned out to be crucial in their
"swords-to-ploughshares" conversion. Weapon producers in southwest
China, for example, now mainly produce motor vehicles and auto
parts. They sold 12 billion yuan (1.5 billion US dollars) worth of
such products last year, 95 percent of their total sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Defense Industry: Turning Swords into Ploughshares (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The following names are familiar to most Chinese: Jialing,
Jianshe and Chang'an. Jialing tops the country's sales list of
motorcycles and is closely followed by Jianshe, another motorcycle
producer, and Chang'an, maker of mini-cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
Cars and motorcycles are actually the two most important
civilian products of China's arms industry. Zhang Junjiu told that
the industry will invest more in the two products in the hope of
making it a mainstay of China's automotive industry.
</P>
<P>
Electronics is another civilian field that the defense industry
has an edge. Mianyang, a medium-sized city in southwest China's
Sichuan province, has become limelight for three former arms
factories there now become giant civilian product makers.
</P>
<P>
Changhong Corp. is the country's biggest television producer
today. The corp. last year made 4.8 million color TV sets, which
replaced foreign brands as best sellers.
</P>
<P>
Huafeng, making electronic plugs, has hundreds of rivals
including those set up by foreign investors. But no one has yet
been able to shake the position of Huafeng as China's king of
electronic plugs.
</P>
<P>
Jiuzhou's strength lies in an ability to produce 700 kinds of
cable TV facilities. Last year, it sold more than one million
terminals and prided itself on taking up one third of the domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
Sales of the three's civilian products accounted for 95 percent
of the total of the country's electronics industry. And their
employees' annual income is more than double the average of
Chinese workers.
</P>
<P>
"We will put more efforts into the development of high-level
civilian products in the next five years," said Cao Gangchuan,
director of the Commission of Science, Technology and Industry for
national Defense under the State Council.
</P>
<P>
With the pledge, more and better civilian products manufactured
by defense industry enterprises will enter ordinary people's homes
and lives. And, with continued production conversion of its
defense industry, China's modernization drive is expected to fare
even better in years to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
