<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Moderately Tight Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to follow
a moderately tight monetary policy well into the next century,
according to a senior Chinese bank official.
</P>
<P>
"We will retain a monetary tight monetary policy in order to
control inflation and ensure sustained, stable and healthy
national economic development," said Shang Fulin, deputy-governor
of the People's Bank of China. Shang made the remarks during a
recent international seminar on the financial systems in China and
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
China's moderately tight monetary policy will remain unchanged
during the Ninth Five-Year Plan Period (1996-2000) and the
foreseeable future thereafter in order to ensure the stability of
the country's currency, according to Shang.
</P>
<P>
Four-odd years of macroeconomic control have led to a decline
in the nation's inflation rate from 21.7 percent in 1994 to 1.8
percent for the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
"macroeconomic policies centered on controlling inflation have
been a major success," said Shang, adding the nation's
macroeconomic environment will continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
Shang predicted that China's annual economic growth rate for
this year will approach 10 percent, with inflation remaining below
five percent.
</P>
<P>
China will record yet another trade surplus this year despite
the recent currency crisis in Southeast Asia, according to another
central bank officials at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials noted that China should learn a lesson from the
crisis and step up its effort to reform exchange rate mechanisms
and adopt measures to eliminate potential inflationary pressures
and financial risks in the process of economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 financial officials, experts and scholars from
China, Mexico, Peru, Chile, Venezuela and a number of other
countries attended the seminar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
