<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Cassava Varieties to Help Uganda Fight Famine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Researchers from China,
Colombia, Uganda and United Kingdom have developed resistant
varieties to cassava mosaic, a disease which destroys the
plant, ''the New Vision'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
Excited local scientists in Namulonge Research Institute in
central Uganda said the planting materials of the new varieties
are being distributed to various districts in the country.
</P>
<P>
Cassava is a buffer plant against famine during long dry
season in Uganda. But a new variety of cassava mosaic has
devastated cassava gardens in the country in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The research team has isolated the new variety in February
this year and the result of the research have been accepted in
April.
</P>
<P>
A report on the results is published in the British journal,
the General Virology, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The research result will save an annual loss of 60,000
hectares of cassava in the country, or some 600,000 tons of the
roots worth 60 billions of Uganda Shillings (some 60 millions
U.S. Dollars), the report said.
</P>
<P>
The disease also causes a 1.5 billion U.S. Dollars loss in
other parts of Africa and on the Indian sub-continent, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
The study was carried out in Dundee, Scotland with study
material from Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The planting material is being multiplied at Namulonge and
Serere research centers in the center before distribution to
farming communities for further multiplication. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
