<HEADLINE> NPC to Examine Enforcement of Agriculture Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's highest legislature
body, announced here today that it will conduct a new round of
supervision on enforcement of Agriculture Law beginning next month.
</P>
<P>
The committee will dispatch three groups of lawmakers to
Jiangxi and Guizhou provinces and the Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region on a ten-day fact-finding mission to examine implementation
of the law which has been in effect since July 1993.
</P>
<P>
Four other provinces, including Guangdong and Liaoning, have
received authorization to conduct internal fact-finding
inspections of local enforcement of the law.
</P>
<P>
The NPC has conducted four annual supervisory inspections of
implementation of the law since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, urged local
governments at various levels to continue paying close attention
to publicizing the law, and called on them to redouble their
efforts to solve urgent problems related to implementation.
</P>
<P>
He called for accelerated efforts to draft relevant rules and
regulations and to standardize the supervision of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Buhe said this particular inspection tour will place priority
on inputs to agriculture, the circulation and distribution of farm
products, and burdens shouldered by farmers.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that special attention should be paid to
scrutinizing and improving problems uncovered in the last three
inspections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
