<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African Efforts to Fight Against Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The criminal investigation
departments of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda have agreed to work
together to combat increased drug trafficking in the region, The
East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting held in the lake town of Entebbe of Uganda last
week, the weekly paper said, the three East African countries
decided to set up a system for communication and exchange of
information relating to narcotics trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attended by criminal investigation department
directors of the three countries pointed out that Uganda had been
made a favorable ground for illicit business in drug trafficking
mainly due to inadequate border controls.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Uganda Anti Narcotics Unit seized more than 258 tons
of cannabis and arrested 298 drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attributed the growing use of East Africa as a
conduit for narcotics in recent years to the liberalization of
trade and lack of sophisticated drug detecting equipment at
points of entry.
</P>
<P>
A source said Ugandan laws are still lenient on drug
traffickers and this may hamper regional efforts to fight the
drug trafficking practice.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, Tanzania has acquired more than eight
sniffer dogs stationed at main points of entry while Kenya has
four and Uganda has only one.
</P>
<P>
The main drugs available in the region are cannabis, heroin,
cocaine, mandrax, metaqualone and khat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
