<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Expanding Green Area Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The green area coverage rate
of Beijing, the Chinese capital, has reached 36.26 percent, with
the figure growing by one percent annually in recent years,
according to an official from Beijing Greening Committee.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has planted 1.8 million trees and 1.3 million square
meters of grass in urban areas this year alone, increasing its
urban green area coverage rate to over 32 percent, or about 7.18
square meters per person.
</P>
<P>
The city has also planted 12.33 million trees across its
suburban plains farmland afforestation network, up 23 percent over
the planned target.
</P>
<P>
Greening projects have greatly improved Beijing's ecological
environment.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has been decorated with millions of potted plants on
the eve of recent major events such as July 1 when China resumed
sovereignty over Hong Kong, as well as Sept. 12 prior to the
opening of the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China. The city will also abound with flowers on Oct. 1, China's
48th National Day.
</P>
<P>
Beijing plans to increase its green area coverage rate in urban
areas to 35 percent, or eight square meters per person, by the end
of this century, according to the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
