<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa's Drive to Promote Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 29 (Xinhua) -- An aggressive marketing
campaign aimed at attracting tourists to the southern African
region has been launched after the approval of the regional
tourism organization charter, the Herald daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Executive director of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) tourism organization Shepard Nyaruwata said in
an interview at the weekend that the region had considerable
tourism potential, which is still to be exploited.
</P>
<P>
"Each country has been trying to promote itself. We are now
looking at selling the region as this will help promote tourism
growth in all countries," said Nyaruwata.
</P>
<P>
SADC ministers responsible for tourism signed the regional
tourism organization charter whose objective is to sell the
region as a tourist haven during this month's Blantyre SADC
summit.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to result in an increase in tourism and
the creation of thousands of jobs in member countries, Nyaruwata
said.
</P>
<P>
Nyaruwata said other regions were developing their industries
at a fast rate and SADC countries would be in a better position
to compete if they were united.
</P>
<P>
"We need to improve the quality of service so that it becomes
uniform in all countries. The tourists should be happy with the
services they get in all SADC countries if we are to maintain the
good name we are trying to build," he said.
</P>
<P>
In order to promote the region's tourism, Zimbabwe will next
month host a SADC investment forum on tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
