<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police to Crack Down on Armed Bandits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
mounted a major security operation in Northeastern Province to
track armed bandits who killed more than 20 local people in the
past week, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted police spokesman Peter Kimanthi as saying
that "we have responded swiftly and are combing the region in
search of these killers."
</P>
<P>
An extensive security operation is under way in areas
surrounding Tog-shabele, said Kamanthi, adding that Kenya Army
personnel are using military aircraft to search for the killers.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that reinforcements had been sent to the aid
of the scattered security personnel in the province to beef up
the team in their tough battle against the well-organized
bandits.
</P>
<P>
In two bloody days last week, 12 people including nine
Administration Police officers were gunned down by the ruthless
bandits when the officers were pursuing them together with their
25 colleagues.
</P>
<P>
A wave of panic sweeping through the Garissa town, capital of
the province, following the rampant killings during the past
week, and local leaders and residents expressed anger and
concerns over the increasing state of insecurity.
</P>
<P>
David Mutemi, Wajir District Commissioner of Northeastern
Province, urged Kenyan Somalis to help the government curb the
infiltration of sophisticated weapons from Somalia.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the recurrence of armed attacks by daring
marauders from the neighboring country posed a major concern to
the government.
</P>
<P>
Mutemi is expected to hand over to residents today some 377
goats stolen by a heavily armed gang and recovered by security
forces last Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
