<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Military to Reconsider Ties with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkish military is
considering whether to exclude Russia from competition in
Turkey's defense projects due to the latter's obstinate position
on missile transfer to Cyprus, local newspaper Daily News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Turkey plans to spend at least 150 billion U.S. dollars in the
next 25 years on modernization programs, which is of interest to
Russia, the paper quoted senior military sources, who declined to
be named, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military is seeking international industrial companies
to bid for these defense projects, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly criticized the Russian-Cypriot missile
deal, saying that the offensive weapons would constitute a
serious threat to Turkey's state security.
</P>
<P>
Russia, which has lost much of the arms markets in eastern
Europe and other regions, insisted on the sale of 150
anti-aircraft S-300 missiles to Cyprus according to a deal signed
by the two countries last January.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military vowed to destroy the missiles by force if
they are finally deployed in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
However, Russian state-controlled company Rosvoorouzhenie,
producer of the S-300 missiles, said that Cyprus, as a sovereign
state, has the right to buy weapons which they need, adding it
had no intention to drop the deal.
</P>
<P>
Russia is reportedly eager to participate in Turkey's 4.5
billion dollar project to produce the third generation tanks and
another 3.5 billion dollar project to produce 145 assault
helicopters as well.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot South and
Turkish Cypriot North since 1974 when Turkish troops seized the
northern third of the island following a failed coup seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey, which has
deployed 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
