<HEADLINE> Demand for Zambia's Non-traditional Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Demand for Zambia's
non-traditional exports has outstripped supply and it is likely
that the country might not be able to meet all the orders, Zambia
Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Export Board of Zambia (EBZ) has decided to go flat out
from next year to rural areas to sensitize people on the vast
opportunities for the non-traditional exports.
</P>
<P>
As demand for the non-traditional exports increases, some
areas in the country are reportedly having a hard time in selling
their produce when in fact they could easily be exported to
European markets, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
During the recent visit to Mbala in northern Zambia, EBZ
acting chief executive Johnson Mwenya found stocks of uncollected
soya beans lying dormant as the owners could not market their
produce.
</P>
<P>
He said the EBZ will work with the Ministry of Agriculture,
Good and Fisheries to take stock of the potential export
products.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, which is expected to take part in the South African
Trade Exposition next month has already participated in over 10
international trade fairs all of which have earned it trade
orders worth millions of Kwacha, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
But these orders are usually not fulfilled as demand outstrips
supply, said Mwenya.
</P>
<P>
Promoting the non-traditional exports, which earned Zambia 310
million U.S. Dollars last year, is part of the government efforts
to diversify the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
