<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Rival Warlords Join Hands Against Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ethnic Uzbek
warlord Abdul Malik and his former boss Rashid Dostum, whom he
ousted four months ago, have agreed to join hands in fighting
against the Islamic Taliban militia, Afghan sources here said
today.
</P>
<P>
Dostum, who returned to Afghanistan in early September after
three months of exile in Turkey, Sunday rushed to Shiberghan,
capital of Afghanistan's northwestern Jowzjan province, and held a
crucial meeting with Malik, the Afghan sources said.
</P>
<P>
The two strongman held lengthy discussions on the prevailing
situation around Mazar-e-Sharif, capital of the next-door Balkh
province and stronghold of Malik and his northern anti-Taliban
alliance, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Dostum and Malik agreed to take joint action
against the Taliban who had been posting serious threats to
Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 kilometers northwest of Kabul, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Dostum and Malik's meeting took place as the Taliban fighters
were poised to launch an all-out attack on Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The militia have claimed they had tightened their stranglehold
of the city after the fresh offensives in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
Dostum, once the strongest warlord in Afghanistan, was forced
to flee the country late May when his right hand-man Malik staged
a sudden revolt against him.
</P>
<P>
Malik briefly sided with the Taliban, allowing them to enter
northern Afghanistan unopposed. However, a few days later, in a
row over power sharing, Malik staged another about-face and drove
the hard-line student militia out again.
</P>
<P>
Later, he formed a new anti-Taliban alliance with Afghanistan's
former military chief Ahmad Masood and the Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat.
The alliance has announced Mazar-e-Sharif as their temporary
capital.
</P>
<P>
However, Malik has failed to win over pro-Dostum elements and
infighting among his forces has put him on the defensive when the
Taliban launched a strong attack on Mazar-e-Sharif earlier this
month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
