<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Loans for Housing Up in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's four building
societies have advanced a record 2.5 billion Zimbabwean Dollars
in new housing mortgages during the last 12 months as demand for
housing countrywide continues to outstrip supply.
</P>
<P>
This was reported today by the daily paper the Herald which
added that currently, one U.S Dollar equals to 12 Zimbabwean
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The largest building society, the Central Africa Building
Society, made a record 880 million Zimbabwean Dollars lending in
its history to housing schemes, while Beverley Building Society,
Founders Building Society and the Zimbabwe Building Society have
also made huge commitments to the housing cause.
</P>
<P>
Results of a recent survey by property consultants, Knight
Frank, show that despite the high cost of borrowing with the
lowest rate currently quoted by building societies at 17.25
percent, demand has been high for low-density houses,
particularly in the low to middle sections of the market.
</P>
<P>
This has in turn pushed up the prices of the houses in the low
to middle sections, with the cheapest low-density houses in
Harare priced at around 600,000 Zimbabwean Dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey in Harare by Knight Frank, the
low-density residential sales market was very buoyant over the
last 12 months, leading to significant increases in values.
</P>
</TEXT>
