<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education For All: Priority of Priorities (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Project Hope, initiated by the China Youth Development
Foundation in 1989 to assist those children forced to drop out of
schooling by poverty, has so far collected a total of 978 million
yuan (117.83 million US dollars) in donations from China and
abroad. Funds have been used to pay for the education of 1.54
million individuals "adopted" by donors who pledge to mail cash on
a regular basis for childrens' tuition via post
offices. Meanwhile, general funds have been used to build 3,600
primary schools in poor villages.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Shengli, one of the first beneficiaries of the Project
Hope, graduated from Shanghai No.1 Normal School last year and
returned to his hometown in north China's Hebei province to teach
in a primary school. "I'll extend my knowledge gained with the
help of social charity to more kids in remote and impoverished
areas," he says.
</P>
<P>
But while special attention is given to boys and girls in
poverty-stricken areas, education of migrants' children has also
come on the agenda. These children have moved with their parents
from the interior areas to urban cities, coastal areas and other
cities on the wave of pursuing opportunities. Estimates suggest
that two to three million of them have reached school age, but
most are barred from attending local schools because they do not
possess the necessary citizenship, let alone the financial ability
to pay.
</P>
<P>
To prevent migrant children joining the ranks of the
illiterate, SEC has called for all the localities concerned to do
their best to provide school education for them. Pilot schemes are
now operative in Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai, Hebei, Zhejiang and
Shenzhen to put these children in school, who have the theoretical
right, if not the practical wherewithal, to receive a
nine-year-long compulsory education.
</P>
<P>
For with education, and only education, will millions more like
Zhou Haimei be able to take the opportunity to develop themselves
and have a better future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
