<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Round of Agriculture Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- It has long been a tradition
for Chinese farmers to raise chickens in their backyards, but a
group of farmers in Guangxi, southwest China financed a chicken
farm a year ago, paving the way for large-scale chicken production,
processing and marketing.
</P>
<P>
Termed as the latest step towards industrialized farming, one
of the new round of China's agriculture reform, the new
company--Guangdong Wen Poultry Co. Ltd., provides farmers with
complete services and then purchases all mature chickens at
protected prices.
</P>
<P>
The practice has established a large specialized group composed
of chicken breeders which are joining hands to face both regional
and national market competitions.
</P>
<P>
The Yulin, Guangxi-based chicken farm is not alone in such
initiatives. A Ministry of Agriculture official in charge of rural
reform and experimental areas noted tens of thousands of rural
enterprises like Guangdong Wen have emerged in China's rural
areas, especially in more developed rural areas over the recent
few years.
</P>
<P>
"The conditions of the socialist market economy have enabled an
increasing number of rural areas to implement industrialized
farming," according to the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Round of Agriculture Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Observers point to the fact that China has introduced new forms
of businesses in industrialized farming and reformed production
systems in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The new production and management methods, which integrate
production and marketing, can be applied to intensive operations
from the standpoint of funding and providing qualified personnel
and technology. The innovative methods have enabled tens of
thousands of farmers to open up the market.
</P>
<P>
China successfully carried out its first round of rural reform
the early 1980s by abolishing the people's communes and
introducing the household contract responsibility system with
remuneration linked to output.
</P>
<P>
The change ushered in a rapid growth period in China's
agriculture production, and created a miracle in worldwide
agricultural history.
</P>
<P>
China's annual grain output has steadily grown from 304.75
billion kg to last year's harvest of 490 billion kg. Such
achievement has been accompanied by marked increases in the output
of cotton, oil crops, meat and aquatics products.
</P>
<P>
Rapid industrial expansion China's vast rural areas have
witnessed in recent years has widely been heralded as the "second
round of agriculture reform".
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, people have also found that the reform alone will
not "thoroughly and effectively" solve some deep-rooted problems
restricting rural development.
</P>
<P>
Related problems include a comparatively low degree of
intensive farming and low operational efficiency, as well as
increasingly profound contradictions between low production and
large markets, and difficulties in both marketing and purchasing
farm produce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
