<HEADLINE> New Round of Agriculture Reform (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The current move in industrialized farming, which agronomists
refer to as the "third round of agriculture reform", has combined
the strong points of the previous reforms in rural areas, and is
expected to yield new breakthroughs in agriculture development
through industrialized ways.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Wen Poultry, for example, has established fodder
production facilities, marketing and service departments, and
hatcheries to integrate production, supply, marketing, scientific
research, industry and trade. Some 230 households join in a
cooperative in raising chickens for the company.
</P>
<P>
By now, the company has provided local farmers with more than
800,000 hatchlings and sold more than 400,000 packaged chickens
over the past year. Farmers have earned 450,000 yuan in total,
with Guangdong Wen earning 580,000 in profits.
</P>
<P>
Yulin, Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, is one of China's many
rural experimental areas. Local officials noted that 50 of the
city's rural breeding enterprises are generating an annual output
value of one million yuan each.
</P>
<P>
Rural enterprises are currently introducing intensive farming
to approximately 10 percent of the city's total land, and some 500
enterprises are developing an average 6.6 ha. each, a local
official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Round of Agriculture Reform (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Many provinces, including Shandong, Henan, Anhui, Zhejiang,
Jiangsu and Guangdong, are also extending the effort to foster
various forms of ownership for rural enterprises in accordance
with local conditions. Related efforts have promoted the
integration of trade, industry and agriculture, as well as the
unified operations of production and marketing.
</P>
<P>
Shandong Province, a forerunner in introducing industrialized
farming, is currently home to some 18,000 rural enterprises
which generated 1996 earnings of over 100 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Central China's Henan Province, yet another of the country's
major agricultural areas, is home to over 15,000 enterprises
directly engaged in production related to farming, forestry,
animal husbandry and fisheries, as well as in processing and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural enterprises in the central Chinese province have
helped more than four million farmers, or 23 percent of the total,
enter the market.
</P>
<P>
In addition, agricultural enterprises featuring both high input
and high efficiency have attracted many farmers willing to invest
in enterprises and carry out highly industrialized farming.
</P>
<P>
He Dong, a farmer in Zhongshan City, south China's Guangdong
Province, has contracted some 20 hectares of paddy fields to grow
rice. Mechanized farming and harvesting equipment have enabled He
to earn more than 400,000 yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
"To till farmland on a relatively large scale, the more you
plant, and the more you'll harvest," local farmers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
