<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education For All: Priority of Priorities (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- When she left school at the
age of 14 to work as a domestic in Beijing, Zhou Haimei, a girl
from rural Hubei, central China, could hardly imagine that six
years later she would be employed as an accountant by a private
company in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
"I'll have more opportunities in Beijing if I know how to
operate computers." says the girl who has used much of her
hard-earned monthly income to fund her own night school education.
</P>
<P>
Zhou was able, but also lucky. She had received seven years'
schooling during which she acquired the ability to learn by
herself before dropping out from school because of poverty. A lot
more are not so lucky as Zhou is.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from the State Education Commission (SEC)
show that in China today, a total of four to five million children
aged 7-11, mostly from remote and rural impoverished areas and
two-thirds of them girls, are prevented from going to school
mainly because of poverty.
</P>
<P>
"Nine-year compulsory education must be made top priority in
order to eradicate illiteracy among young and middle-aged people,"
urged Chinese vice-premier Li Lanqing in an article in 1996 to
mark the 10th anniversary of the issuance of the "Law on
Compulsory Education."
</P>
<P>
Increasing its funding by some 20 percent annually, China has
spent a total of 602.5 billion yuan (72.59 billion US dollars) on
education over the past five years (1992-1996). In 1996 alone, a
total of 214.4 billion yuan (25.83 billion US dollars) was spent
on education, 99.4 billion yuan (11.97 billion US dollars) of
which came from the government budget.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, 98.81 percent of school-aged children had actually
enrolled in primary schools, up one percent on the 1990
figure.
</P>
<P>
Four million illiterates per year aged between 15-47 have
cast off their handicaps since 1990. Last year, 4.06 million
people in this age group mastered reading and writing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wu Yi Outlines Principles for Asia-Europe Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- China's Foreign Trade and
Cooperation Minister Wu Yi today outlined China's position and
principles for Asia-Europe cooperation in trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Wu unveiled the guidelines at the two-day session of the
Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) which closed today in the city of
Chiba, near Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Wu said there are wide differences among ASEM members in the
level of economic development, trade and investment regime, social
system and cultural tradition and therefore cooperation between
these countries should be on the basis of mutual respect,
recognition of the existing differences.
</P>
<P>
It would be unrealistic to stress too much on unified action,
Wu noted, adding that cooperation should be guided by the
following three principles.
</P>
<P>
-- Equality, mutual benefit and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
Interests of members in different development stages should be
taken into consideration and the principle of equitable and
balanced interest should be reflected in real action.
</P>
<P>
-- Non-discrimination.
</P>
<P>
Any preferential trade and investment policy currently enjoyed
by ASEM members should be extended to any country, whether it is
or is not an ASEM member. Existing discriminatory trade practice
and investment barriers should be abolished as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
-- Slow but steady progress.
</P>
<P>
"Wu suggests cooperating in trade and investment facilitation
first because here little disagreement is involved. This should
be followed by efforts to remove barriers and obstacles aimed at
promoting trade and capital flow.
</P>
<P>
To further explore the potential of cooperation, every channel
of cooperation available should be fully utilized," she said.
</P>
<P>
Though there is quite a lot trade and investment flow between
the two regions, the normal trade order is being undermined by
man-made discriminatory trade barriers in some countries, Wu noted.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that regular consultations on trade barriers should be
held among ASEM members and other view-exchanging means should be
explored in preparation for the ultimate elimination of these
trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
Economic ministers from 25 countries attended the meeting, the
first of its kind since the ASEM was launched last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Rejects EU Proposed Plan on Greenhouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Australia today released a
paper rejecting a proposal by the European Union (EU) for a 15
percent reduction by developed countries in greenhouse gas
emission from 1990 to 2010.
</P>
<P>
Australia would not contribute more than other countries to
resolve the greenhouse gas emission crisis, Australian Foreign
Minister Alexander Downer said here today.
</P>
<P>
Australia's Foreign Affairs and Trade Department today released
the paper in which Australia argued its case against binding gas
emission targets ahead of the December climate conference in
Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
The paper reaffirmed Australia's rejection of the greenhouse
gas reduction plan proposed by the EU.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly we have made it clear that type of proposition (made
by the EU) is unacceptable," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to make a fair contribution and that is what
the paper we're releasing today illustrates," the foreign minister
told Australian Broadcasting Corporation Radio.
</P>
<P>
The paper, apparently part of the publicity campaign by the
Australian government to lobby support for its position on the
greenhouse gas issue, said Australia could lose offshore up to
8.64 billion U.S. dollars from 48.96 billion dollars' worth of
planned energy projects if it agreed to uniform international
greenhouse gas emission targets.
</P>
<P>
It said nearly 90,000 jobs, to be created by energy-related
projects, would be at risk. Unemployment has been a chronic
problem for Australia, where the annual average jobless rate has
been about 8 percent for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard has failed to win support
from his counterparts in the United States and Japan on the
greenhouse gas reduction issue during their talks over the past
several months.
</P>
<P>
Downer denied Australia was isolated in its stance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
