<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Export Earnings Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's exports improved
during the first half of this year, with earnings rising 20
percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, Sri Lanka's export earnings reached 119
billion rupees (2 billion U.S. dollars), compared with 99 billion
rupees (1.68 billion dollars) in the corresponding 1996 period,
the Export Development Board (EDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
Textiles and garments, contributing 57 billion rupees (about 1
billion dollars) to the earnings, remained the key items on
foreign markets. Diamonds, gems and jewelry posted 6 billion
rupees (102 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector earned 21 billion rupees (356 million
dollars) while fishery and petroleum products recorded 4 billion
rupees (68 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The EDB said that the rapid development of the industrial
sector was a result of attractive incentives offered by the
government in the last three budget years. Many industries have
undergone expansion and modernization, it said.
</P>
<P>
A 24 percent growth in the manufacturing sector and a 20
percent growth in the agricultural sector are expected this year,
according to the EDB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
