<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5,000-Year-Old Human Grave Found in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A human grave site believed
to be 5,000 years old has been found in southern Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Srian Deraniyagala, director of the Archaeology Department,
said today that the discovery was made about a month ago at a
mining lagoon in Kataragama district in the south of Uva Province.
</P>
<P>
The department was informed about the discovery by villagers in
the area.
</P>
<P>
Initial excavation has revealed that human skeletons and heaps
of shells were buried in the grave.
</P>
<P>
The exact period the site may have belonged to has yet to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
Experts will begin main excavation this week. It is estimated
the whole excavation would last for two to three months.
</P>
<P>
Deraniyagala said it was likely that there was a link between
the stone age and the pre-historic period.
</P>
<P>
"If there is any presence of metal or ceramic we will be able
to date the skeletons," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the skeletons may apply to Sri Lanka's pre-historic
men.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka would seek foreign expertise to carry out a joint
analysis of the skeletons, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
