<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues To Open in Post-Deng Era (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- For China, 1997 will go down
in history as a year of great sorrow and jubilation. Deng
Xiaoping, the chief architect of China's opening policy and
reforms, died in February and on July 1, Hong Kong was returned to
China, ending a national humiliation of more than 150 years.
</P>
<P>
Deng advanced the opening policy back in the late 1970s. This
policy, hand-in-hand with economic reforms, has brought China
unprecedented prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The opening policy will continue after Deng's death. Speaking
at Deng's memorial meeting on February 25, President Jiang Zemin
pledged to follow Deng's teachings and "develop an all-directional
and multi-layer pattern of opening up ... and actively participate
in international economic technological cooperation and
competition."
</P>
<P>
China has benefited enormously from the opening policy over the
past 18 years. By 1996 the country's gross national product has
registered a 5.4-fold increase over 1978 when the opening policy
was initiated. For the 1.2 billion Chinese, the policy means not
only sufficient food and clothing but also consumer goods of a
much greater variety and better quality. They may have access to
things they never dreamed of owning in the past, ranging from
color TVs and telephones to air-conditioners and even private cars.
</P>
<P>
The opening policy first gave birth to four special economic
zones along the Chinese coast: Shenzhen bordering Hong Kong,
Zhuhai near Macao, Shantou in southeastern Guangdong and Xiamen
facing Taiwan. In 1984, 14 more coastal cities were opened to
foreign investment. In 1988, the 33,900-square-kilometer Hainan,
China's second largest island, was made the largest special
economic zone.
</P>
<P>
The second round of opening began in 1992, prompted by Deng's
inspection tour of Shenzhen, China's first special economic zone,
during which he called for accelerated pace of the country's
economic development. Following this historic tour, the Yangtze
River Valley was opened. Pudong New Area of Shanghai, an area as
large as Singapore, is expected to develop into an international
financial center and a high-tech development area. And Suzhou
Industrial Park near Shanghai was also established by the Chinese
and Singaporean governments.
</P>
<P>
All China's interior provincial capitals, except Lhasa of the
Tibet Autonomous Region, were open in 1992. Border regions were
also opened as 14 economic cooperation zones have been set up in
areas bordering countries including the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea, Russia, Myanmar and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, China had approved 285,000 foreign-funded
enterprises, almost half of which had gone into operation. The
aggregate direct foreign investment has increased to 175 billion
US dollars, making China the second biggest recipient of
international investment in the world after the United States.
</P>
<P>
With its total imports and exports amounting to 290 billion US
dollars, China ranked 11th among the world's top trading nations
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserves have kept growing along with
the development of foreign trade, to 117.8 billion US dollars by
the end of May, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues to Open in Post-Deng Era (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's opening policy has persisted with and without Deng at
the helm. Jiang Zemin noted that "opening to the outside world is
an essential condition for China to achieve its socialist
modernization," when addressing at Deng's memorial meeting. He
quoted Deng as saying that "the current world is an open one, that
China's development is inseparable from the world, and that it is
imperative to pursue the policy of opening to the outside world on
the basis of persisting in self-reliance."
</P>
<P>
Not only geographically, but also in the sense that practically
all the economic sectors, China opens its banking, information and
other service industries to foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
China's policy makers are planning to "remake" the special
economic zones, which have pioneered the implementation of the
opening policy. The most significant policy change is the on-going
process of shifting to national treatment for foreign investors in
China from the practice of giving tax privileges and other
preferential treatment offered to foreign investors as in the
first few years after the opening policy was introduced.
</P>
<P>
This will compel the special economic zones to depend more and
more on their own economic strength and initiatives for
development, rather than on policy privileges given them by the
state which were deemed as necessary in the first few years of
their operation.
</P>
<P>
Beginning April 1996, foreign-funded enterprises could no
longer enjoy exemption of custom duties for their imported
manufacturing equipment. Meanwhile, China has reduced its tariff
rates to an average of 15 percent from 35.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
This will make foreign-funded enterprises compete with Chinese
enterprises on a more equal footing. China will gradually allow
foreign companies to play a greater role in fields where they used
to be more or less restricted such as mining, banking, retail
sales and insurance, said Lin Qihui, an official at the State
Council Office in charge of Special Economic Zones.
</P>
<P>
Now that Hong Kong has returned, Lin told that China's
relations with the rest of the world "will definitely become
closer."
</P>
<P>
In striving for development, he said that the country will take
the best advantage of Hong Kong's status as a world financial,
shipping, information and trade center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Speed Up Yangtze River Harnessing (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a matter of fact, conservation work started as early as the
1950s, but it went very slowly. In 1989, the country adopted a Key
Harnessing Plan for Soil Erosion on the Upper Reaches of the
Yangtze, which accelerates the harnessing speed.
</P>
<P>
Since then, 46,000 sq.km. of eroded areas have been brought
under control, and 1.23 million ha of trees had been planted on
the upper reaches by the end of 1996, raising the afforestation
rate to 41.1 percent, from the 22.8 percent at the end of the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
Li Bin, the Ministry of Forestry official, says that if the
Yangtze valley is brought under control at the current rate of
12,000 sq.km. per year, it would take six decades. But, noticing
the frequency and the destruction of natural disasters, some
ministries proposed several times that the harnessing plan be
completed earlier.
</P>
<P>
One source reports that the communications and construction
ministries and the National Environmental Protection Agency (NEPA)
will soon adopt a joint regulation to control pollution caused by
garbage from boats, untreated solid waste, bringing the water
quality up to a decent level. And a protection plan covering the
Yangtze as a whole will also come out in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
