<HEADLINE> Thailand's Rice Exports to Fall Short of Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's total volume of
rice exports this year will fall short of forecasts, according to
Thai Foreign Trade Department Director-General Pracha
Charutrakulchai.
</P>
<P>
Rice export in 1997 was earlier set at 5.35 million tons, but
is now expected to be 4.8-4.9 million tons, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, exports of jasmine rice increased
significantly and its price soared because of a high demand in
East Asia markets.
</P>
<P>
However, during the past few months exports of jasmine rice
decreased as adulteration with low-quality rice caused the
cancellation of many orders.
</P>
<P>
Rice export value for this year is expected to reach the target
of 47 billion baht (1.29 billion U.S. dollars), because high-grade
rice, including jasmine rice, is still receiving favorable prices
overseas, the Bangkok Post today quoted Pracha as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
