<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia's Foreign Trade Grows Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia says its foreign
trade has grown rapidly since the United Nations Security Council
lifted sanctions against the country in October last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest data released by the Yugoslav Statistic
Bureau, Yugoslavia's exports totaled 1.454 billion U.S. dollars in
the first eight months this year, an increase of 27.6 percent over
the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Its imports during this period amounted to 2.916 billion
dollars, up 20.2 percent over the corresponding period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
The overall trade embargo imposed by the U.N. Security Council
in May 1992 had crippled the Yugoslav economy before its
suspension about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia's major exports include nonferrous metals, steel
products, pig iron, tobacco, vegetables and fruits while its major
imports include oil and other raw industrial materials.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia maintains trade ties with a total of 113 countries,
with Italy, Macedonia, Germany, Russia and the Bosnian Serb
Republic as major trade partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
