<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefit from Medi-Care System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Du Yuxia, a 30-year-old
farmer, was relieved to learn that the cooperative medical care
program would pay one third of her 1,200 yuan medical bill, when
she was hospitalized for ectopic pregnancy in early 1995.
</P>
<P>
In Du's village, each person, young or old, pays 11 yuan (1.3
US dollars) a year to sign up to the cooperative program. It's like
saving for a rainy day.
</P>
<P>
"The system is an effective way by which farmers help each
other to reduce the financial risk of illness," said Zheng
Chaoyang, an official with the Medical Policy Department of the
Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said individuals contribute the bulk of funds to the
cooperative system, while village committees input small amounts
from their collective funds and township enterprises. Governments
at higher levels also provide a little funding.
</P>
<P>
China's rural residents, unlike the majority of their urban
counterparts who continue to enjoy medical insurance provided by
their work units, are often faced with unexpected medical fees.
</P>
<P>
In poor countryside areas, the term "going to hospital' soon
become a metaphor for hard times. Statistics from the Ministry of
Health indicate that 30 percent of those living below the
poverty line become impoverished as a result of crippling medical
bills.
</P>
<P>
"To date the cooperative system has proved to be the most
effective way of providing a financial helping hand to people
whose health fails them," said Zhang. But he stressed that
participation is only voluntary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefit from Medi-Care System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Overseeing the setting up of cooperative medical care system is
a major task in the Chinese government's commitment to achieve the
World Health Organization's (WHO) "Health for All" standards,
which must be gained by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health issued basic guidelines for health care
in rural areas in 1990 to improve provision and set minimum
standards.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines call for sufficient government financial input,
health care education, the establishment of medical care clinics
in villages, the use of clean water, provision of cleaner
lavatories and the spread of cooperative medical care systems.
</P>
<P>
Main target components of actual health care include achieving
a reduction in the mortality rate of new-born babies, improving
ante- and post-natal care, and scoring higher immunization rates
to protect children from childhood diseases.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines require administrators to recruit 50 to 60
percent of a county's populace to the cooperative medical care
system.
</P>
<P>
Although it is feasible for the more than 2,000 counties in
China to set up medical care systems by 2000, Zhang predicted
that not all villages can meet the target.
</P>
<P>
But he thought that more than half of the country's villages
will realize this goal by 2000. Currently, 17 percent of villages
have cooperative systems.
</P>
<P>
But to farmers like Du Yuxia who have benefited from the
program, participation is undoubtedly a good choice. "It's a very
reasonable system. We deposit, and age makes it certain that one
day we'll have to benefit from it," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
