<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0200 GMT, September 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish troops continued cross-border operations
against the Kurdish militants in northern Iraq, despite strong
criticism from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
A number of camps of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party, or
PKK, were destroyed in a week of air raids and ground offensives
by the Turkish troops, the Anatolia News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish fighter-bombers carried out an air strike on 15
suspected PKK camps Thursday in northern Iraq where more than
1,000 militants were reportedly gathering in preparation for
winter offensives into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
More than 8,000 Turkish troops, backed by 130 tanks, crossed
into northern Iraq to reinforce the units already stationed there
to wipe out PKK rebel camps. Anatolia said 138 rebels have been
killed so far.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- An American out-of-control earth observation
satellite burned up in the atmosphere Sunday, the U.S. Space
Command said.
</P>
<P>
The Lewis spacecraft, which started tumbling days after being
launched in August, crashed into the atmosphere at 27,000 kph and
burned up at 11:58 GMT over the southern Atlantic Ocean off the
coast of Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Agency (NASA) has
launched an independent investigation into the loss of the
mission, which was to have monitored land use and pollution.
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Economic ministers from Asian and European countries
concluded Sunday their first meeting in Chiba, near Tokyo, and
called for closer ties between the two continents for sustainable
growth.
</P>
<P>
To expand trade and investment flows between the two regions,
the ministers from 25 Asian and European countries set principles
and common policy tasks at the two-day session of the Asian-Europe
Meeting (ASEM).
</P>
<P>
In a chairman's statement issued after the meeting, the
ministers said ASEM economic cooperation will "reinforce the
underlying sound economic structures" and "contribute to the
robustness of the ASEM economies." 
</P>
</TEXT>
