<HEADLINE> China to Speed Up Harnessing Yangtze River (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government plans
to speed up water and soil conservation and ecological
improvements along the Yangtze river, the country's longest.
</P>
<P>
According to a new plan by the Ministry of Water Resources for
the period 1997 to 2010, by that time 218,000 sq.km. of the
Yangtze's total area will be under control, bringing ecological
deterioration under control. An area of 562,000 sq.km. of the
river is now hit by soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to speed up improving the river over the next
two decades," said an official with the ministry's Water
Conservancy Department, who says it will adopt such measures as
reclaiming farmland on mountainsides, small-scale water control
facilities, and more protective farming instead of destroying
soil quality.
</P>
<P>
Only when the amount of forested area is above 60 percent on
the upper and middle reaches of the river will a sound ecological
preservation system be formed, according to Li Bin, who is in
charge of the Ministry of Forestry's Yangtze Shelter-Forest
project.
</P>
<P>
So, the ministry will plant 14 million hectares of trees
along the river over the next 30 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that more than seven billion yuan (840 million
US dollars) will be needed for the huge project of the two
ministries for the 1997-2010 period alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
