<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Quake Toll Rises to 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- At least 17 people were
killed and 331 others injured in the tectonic earthquake measuring
6.4 on the Richter scale which jolted Indonesia's south Sulawesi
province Sunday, Antara news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports put the casualties at 12 dead and dozens
injured.
</P>
<P>
The quake, which started at 9:38 a.m. local time and lasted for
several minutes, hit a number of districts such as Pinrang,
Pare-Pare, Sidrap and Polewali as well as Ujungpandang, capital of
the province.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake is located at 3.85 degrees of the
south latitude and 119.65 degrees of the east longitude at a depth
of 300 kilometers, some 54 kilometers southeast of Polewali
district, an official of the local meteorological and geophysics
office was quoted as saying Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Together with armed forces personnel, evacuation teams were
sent to the affected areas to evacuate the quake victims to the
nearest hospitals.
</P>
<P>
About 331 victims who suffered from injuries were taken to
hospitals or public health centers, reports said.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, the number of houses destroyed by the
earthquake was 415 houses, 10 worship houses and 10 cars.
</P>
<P>
The quake also reportedly hit Pinang and Majene districts
measuring four on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
After the first tremor at 9:38 a.m., at least six aftershocks
had been recorded up to 16:37 p.m. with a varied intensity
measuring from six to 2.4 on the Richter scale, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There is no immediate estimate on the total loss incurred by
the quake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
