<HEADLINE> China to Speed Up Yangtze River Harnessing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
These steps are imperative to ensure the proper functioning of
the gigantic Three Gorges Dam, the world's largest hydro-electric
power program, mainly for sand reduction in the Yangtze. The Three
Gorges project will be completed by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
And, just by 2030 or so, the long-term plan is expected to tame
the Yangtze and completely stop the disasters thanks to the effort.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, guaranteeing the safety of the
economically-viable plateau on the middle and lower reaches needs
to be considered, and central and western areas developed, arable
land saved, and the ecology of the Yangtze improved.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze is 6,300 kilometers long, and its valley covers
nearly a fifth of China's territory. It is a key agricultural and
industrial area.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, however, the area has suffered from severe
water loss and soil erosion. This is especially true on the
352,000 sq.km. of the upper reaches, which includes two
tributaries, the Jinsha and Jialing, where much of the land has
been affected by soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
Floods, droughts, mud and rocks have caused repeated problems
and the scope of these disasters is widening. The Chinese continue
to worry about whether the Yangtze will become a second Yellow
river, meaning serious concern in mounting silt.
</P>
</TEXT>
