<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Reforms Progress In China's Countryside (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- With 964 votes, Li Zhenming,
a 42-year-old farmer, has beaten his rival Xu Jianli and won the
election of chairman of Dongxia Village Committee in east China's
Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Xu Jianli, 33, regretted that he lost the election with only
261 voting for him. "Nevertheless the election reflected the
villagers' will," he says, adding that he will campaign again next
time, when he will try to win.
</P>
<P>
Direct elections for leading members of village committees have
been held every three years in rural China since 1987.
</P>
<P>
"Direct and democratic elections are a key political reform in
China's rural areas, putting an end to the practice of village
officials being appointed by township governments," says Wang
Zhenyao, a senior official with the Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The village constitutes the lowest administrative level in
China. Sometimes one village can be composed of a cluster of
natural sub-villages. An average village has a population of
1,000. A big one can have several thousand people.
</P>
<P>
Up above villages in China's pyramidic power structure are
townships, counties, cities or prefectures, provinces and the
central government.
</P>
<P>
As 80 percent of China's 1.2 billion people are rural dwellers,
villages are the most intimate communities for the most of the
Chinese to live in.
</P>
<P>
In feudal China, the village was ruled by the richest or the
patriarch of the biggest clan in the community. Ordinary villagers
had no say whatsoever except to turn over land rent and serve
corvee.
</P>
<P>
After New China was founded in 1949, farmers in villages began
to have some say. Yet in some cases it did not go beyond raising
their hands for whatever the village heads had on mind.
</P>
<P>
And the village heads were often nominated, if not directly
appointed, by the administrative bodies above and "voted" in the
village leadership by villagers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Reforms Progress In China's Countryside (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Now the practice of the majority being led by a few is gone, as
villagers are encouraged to nominate their candidates and the
candidates have to campaign for the posts in the village
leadership.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese law, with the backing of five
villagers a candidate can be nominated. Then some villager
representatives will be elected to decide on the formal
candidates.
</P>
<P>
In some places, all the eligible villagers, namely those at or
above age 18, directly pick the normal candidates by voting.
</P>
<P>
More than 15,000 village committees in Fujian Province have
been or will be re-elected this year. And across China, there are
more than 930,000 village committees, in charge of local affairs,
settling disputes, and safeguarding social security.
</P>
<P>
In Dongxia Village, where 1,463 villagers are eligible to vote
this year, 25 representatives were elected in March to decided on
formal candidates for the village head from among four nominees,
who all presented their programs to run the village. Li and Xu
passed as the finalists to confront the voting by the whole
village.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee the villagers' democratic rights, privacy for
those marking their voting papers is ensured. Cai Shuhua, a
50-year-old woman in Fashi Village neighboring with Dongxia,
received ballot papers together with her husband and two children
before they went into the restricted access room in turn.
</P>
<P>
After casting their votes, the family went off to work in
village factories. "We filled in our ballots independently, and
don't know each other's choice," she says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestine to Hold talks in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and Palestine Liberation Organization Secretary-General
Mahmoud Abbas are scheduled to hold talks here Monday in a joint
effort to revive the peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. official said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
host the meeting after she meets with Levy in the morning in a
hotel here.
</P>
<P>
The talks are a new development following Albright's trip to
the Middle East three weeks ago. During that visit, she failed to
persuade Israel to change its policy of building Jewish
settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has recently stepped up blockade of the
Palestinian autonomous areas and arrests of "terrorists," which
aggravated tensions with Palestine and drew more criticism from
the outside including the United States.
</P>
<P>
The announcement Wednesday by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
to build another 300 Jewish homes in the West Bank town of Efrat
fueled the criticism.
</P>
<P>
Calling Netanyahu's move "regrettable" and "unhelpful,"
Albright told reporters here Thursday "I would like to see a 'time
out', and I am calling on Prime Minister Netanyahu to honor
that 'time out'."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton Administration's envoy to the Middle East Dennis
Ross has reportedly spent much of the week meeting with Israeli
and Palestinian delegations in Washington in an effort to smooth
the way for Monday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process came to a standstill in March
after Israel decided to go ahead with Jewish settlement expansion
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
It slid into deeper crisis after two suicide bombings ripped
off Jerusalem markets in July and September, killing 25 people.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has stopped giving back lands to Palestine as
stipulated by the previous peace accords, demanding Palestine
crack down on terrorist infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
