<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Reforms Progress In China's Countryside (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fujian Province took the lead in the country with regard to
developing standardized election methods in rural areas in the
mid-1980s. By the end of November 1997 the province will witness
the completion of the sixth round of elections in its villages.
</P>
<P>
Over the years across the country, procedures have matured and
are now reasonably standard and unified, says Wang Zhenyao of the
Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Since the elections respect villagers' democratic rights and
reflect their will, farmers are enthusiastic about the democratic
exercise and value their right to play an active part.
</P>
<P>
In Fujian's Meishan Village, more than a thousand villagers
reportedly traveled back home to exercise their democratic rights
on April 12.
</P>
<P>
For the convenience of those living in remote farmsteads,
mobile ballot boxes and even postal voting have been made
available. On the whole, turnouts have been very high with around
90 percent of those eligible casting votes, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
"The greatest aspect of direct rural elections in China is that
villagers have the widespread right to actually nominate
candidates," says Wang Zhongtian, a professor with the Party
School of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China,
adding that an election without the right to nomination cannot be
taken as a truly effective and democratic election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
