<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weather Research Projects on Horizon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- China will launch four
large-scale meteorological research and experimental projects in
the coming year as a part of its meteorological system
modernization drive, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Wen Kegang, director-general of China Meteorological
Administration (CMA), announced the projects as the Second Series
of Atmospheric Experiments on the 3,000-meter high Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, South China Sea Monsoon Research, Research into South
China's Tropical Storms, and a Study of the Air Flow
Energy-Moisture Content Change Cycle over the Huaihe, China's
third largest river.
</P>
<P>
These research projects, the largest of their kind in the
country, will be sponsored and organized by the Chinese
Government, Wen said.
</P>
<P>
Three of them will focus on climate changes, while the other
will contribute to research on meso-scale meteorological systems
-- the movement and changes of weather conditions in areas within
a radius ranging from 20 to 250 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The four experiments will be inter-related, as the research
projects to be carried out in the South China and the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau are expected to lay down a broad foundation
for the basic scientific experiments scheduled to be conducted in
South China and the Huaihe River, Wen said.
</P>
<P>
The programs will be supported by wide-ranging international
co-operation with the involvement of meteorological experts from
the United States, Japan, Australia, South Korea and Southeast
Asian countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970929.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New China Enjoys Overall Progress in Past 48 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The return of Hong Kong and
the 15th CPC Natioanl Congress have enriched celebrations of the
48th birthday for China, which has seen great political,
economic and cultural progresses since it was founded in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Chinese all over the world are jubilant about the return of
Hong Kong to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has returned to a vigorously developing motherland,
whose continuously high growth rate of ten percent a year will
bring Hong Kong more opportunities to get further development,"
said Prof. Liu Wei of the Economic School of Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
The 15th CPC National Congress, which was held in September,
has laid down guidelines for China to enter the new century with
even greater momemtum for developement, according to delegates of
the congress.
</P>
<P>
At 48, China can be proud of what it has achieved in many
sectors. It has succeeded in feeding 1.2 billion people, or
one-fifth of the world's population, on less than seven percent of
the world's arable land.
</P>
<P>
This year China has had another bumper harvest of summer grain
-- for three years in a row -- with a total output of 118 million
tons, 3.5 percent over the previous summer.
</P>
<P>
With its GNP reaching 6,779.5 billion yuan (816.8 billion US
dollars) in 1996, which ranked 7th in the world, China is no
longer a nation to be bullied.
</P>
<P>
A fairly complete industrial system has been built over the
past 48 years. The country is the biggest steel producer in the
world today, with an annual output that exceeds 100 million tons.
Its output of steel in 28 days exceeds old China's total
production of 7.6 million tons in 58 years, from 1890 to 1948.
</P>
<P>
China is also one of the world's biggest producers of coal,
cotton cloth, building and sanitary ceramics and TV sets. Her
space industry, started 40 years ago, is capable of commerical
launch services for other countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people are better educated and healthier. In 1946,
the peak year of general education in old China, there were only
52 primary school pupils and three high school students among
every 1,000 Chinese. In 1996, proportions rose to 113 and 57
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to tremendous efforts to promote public health, the
infant mortality rate is now 36.4 per thousand, against 200 before
1949; the maternal fatality rate is down from 1,500 to 62 per
100,000; various infectious, endemic and parasitic diseases have
been effectively controlled; and the average life expectancy has
doubled from 35 to 70.8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
