<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Develop Vaccine Against Computer Viruses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. military plans to
develop a software that allows computers to imitate the human
immune system in fighting off computer viruses, hackers and
information warfare attacks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force and the Pentagon's Defense Advanced Research
Projects Agency (DARPA) plans to develop the software in two years
with around one million dollars in budget, the Defense News weekly
said in its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
As the Pentagon relys on information technology to provide
future tactical advantage, defending against cyber attacks has
become a top priority.
</P>
<P>
A General Accounting Office report released in May said 559
cyber attacks were reported in 1995, with 14,000 expected to be
reported in 1999, based on the percentage of annual increases, the
weekly said.
</P>
<P>
A Defense Science Board report earlier this year advised the
Pentagon to increase spending on cyber attack protection by 3
billion dollars during the next five years.
</P>
<P>
An antivirus program modeled on the human immune system offers
several advantages over current computer protection systems, the
weekly said.
</P>
<P>
The software program would be designed to emulate the
properties of the human immune system that enables it to recognize
virtually any foreign substance anywhere in the body no matter how
the invader enters.
</P>
<P>
Software modeled on the immune system would respond instantly
and efficiently to cyber virus or attacks anywhere on a network,
eventually offering the Defense Department a distinct advantage in
fighting the thousands of annual cyber attacks on its systems.
</P>
<P>
The software will become more valuable as the Pentagon moves
toward a system of systems, which means virtually all computers,
whether on weapons system platforms or personal computers, will be
compatible and connected, noted the Defense News. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
