<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Check Inflows of Foreign Job-Seekers, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The German government is
planning measures to drastically limit the legal or illegal
employment of foreigners who come from non-European-Union states,
a German newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the German newspaper Bild am Sonntag,
an initiative to be put forward by German labour minister Norbert
Bluem would seek to tighten up the entry requirements for foreign
job-seekers, to gradually reduce the number of seasonal workers
and to impose a total ban on employment for asylum-seekers.
</P>
<P>
The plan would be reviewed next week by social-politics experts
of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's ruling Christian Democratic Union
(CDU) and Christian Soical Union (CSU) parties.
</P>
<P>
The news report also quoted a German parliament member as
saying that despite an economic upswing, the German job market had
not seen any major improvement so far. Part of the reason was that
the job market was loaded by up to 250,000 foreign job-seekers
annually.
</P>
<P>
"We want to rigorously control such inflows with our measures,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
