<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-28 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Normalizing Turkey-Greece Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem said today that Greece should adopt vigorous measures
for the normalization of the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press upon returning to Istanbul from the 52nd
U.N. General Assembly in New York, Cem said his meeting with Greek
counterpart Theodoros Pangalos failed to create a positive
atmosphere for talks between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing Greek focus on a disputed island, Cem said that
Turkey suggested the Aegean problem, including sharing of sea-bed
riches, sovereignty over the Aegean and territorial waters, be
discussed as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Cem said Turkey could not accept Greek view that the Aegean
problem can not be solved before a solution of the small island is
reached.
</P>
<P>
Imia, or Kardak called by the Turks, is an uninhabited islet
in the eastern Mediterranean Sea which brought the two traditional
rivals to the brink of war last year.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish foreign minister reiterated that Turkey would be
willing to seek a solution to the thorny Aegean problem peacefully
with the Greek government.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over the sovereignty of a
number of Aegean islands in addition to the protracted issue of
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been mounting in their relations because of the
possible transfer of Russian-made missiles to Cyprus, which
sparked strong criticism from Turkey and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkey accused Greece of encouraging the Cypriot government to
purchase the anti-aircraft missiles, saying it would negatively
affect the settlement of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece support rival ethnic groups in the
Mediterranean island which has been divided since Turkey landed
troops there in the wake of a pro-Athens coup in 1974. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
